Once oil is shimmering, add in onions and garlic and cook for about 3-5 minutes, moving frequently. You want them to get soft and starting to turn translucent, but ideally not browning or frizzling here.
Add in the tomato paste and pumpkin puree and stir to combine.

Pour in vodka and let that bubble up and simmer off for about 5 minutes. You want the alcohol to burn off! You can always sniff the steam to get an idea if there is still alcohol burning off or not… you’ll know if it is!
Time to pour in and cook your pasta! Don’t forget to reserve 1/4 pasta water if you’re straining the whole pot.
Back to the sauce, lower the heat to medium/low and add in 1 tablespoon butter at a time, stirring until fully melted between the additions.
Add in the nutmeg, mixie mix.
Then pour in the heavy cream, mix to combine.
Then add parm, mix to combine. And at this point you need to taste for seasoning! Each parm is going to have a different salinity level so use your best judgement, but I used 1 tsp salt. Mixie mix!
Then I like to strain the pasta using a spider directly into the sauce. This ensures that extra pasta water is getting added in.
Plate it with some extra good quality olive oil on top, some more parm, and some fresh cracked black pep.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Pumpkin Alla Vodka Sauce
Description:
A twist on my usual ~vodka sauce~, but this time with a Fall, Pumpkin twist. 🍂

It has all the comfy cozy feelz of a tradish vodka sauce, but lil fun and special. 

I used some cutie butternut squash pastas from @traderjoes, but you can obviously use whatever you want. 💃🏼

Top it with chicken, ground beef, or some sausages for some protein baby.

ingredients.Name: pickles, hot, dill, sweet, anything works

directions.Direction: Heat up a large pot or dutch oven over medium-high heat. Add in 1 tbsp oil (olive, ghee, tallow, camel, whatever you prefer!) and let that melt/heat up.

Add the ground beef in chunks. As always, you want to make sure there is some space between the chunks to encourage browning and not steaming. Season with some salt and pepper. Do not move around once it's in the pan and let cook for 5-7 minutes, or until deeply browned and crispy.

Once that first side is browned, lower the heat to medium and use a spoon to break up the beef. Cook for another 1-2 minutes, but you don't need to cook all the way through since it'll continue cooking in the sauce later. Use a slotted spoon to remove and set aside.
Add in the diced onions and pepper and cook for 5-7 minutes or until soft, but not browning.

Push the onions and garlic over to the side and add the remaining 1 tbsp oil to that empty space and add in the WHOLE can of tomato paste. We want that to cook for about 2-4 minutes or until the color goes from bright red to a deeper, more brick like red. Use your spoon to move it around and mix it about to make sure allllll dat paste gets cooked. This will help take some of that acidic flavor out of the paste.
Lower the heat to medium-low and stir everything together. Add in the garlic, chili powder, smoked paprika, and onion powder and stir once again. This will quickly help toast/bloom the spices.

Immediately add in the broth plus one cup of water (I measure these out together in a large liquid measuring cup so I can just pour it straight in) Mixie mix that together until it is smooth and no clumps remain. About 1 minute.

Add in the worcestershire, mustard, maple syrup, soy sauce, and the reserved ground beef and mixie mix to combine. Let this simmer on medium-low for about 15-20 minutes, or until the sauce has reduced significantly. As you're cooking it down just think, how messy is too messy? It's really a choose your own mess adventure thing. I don't have to season mine with extra salt, but just give it a taste and see if all your ingredients make sense and if you need extra salt.

While that's cooking down you can toast your buns! I like to use about 1/2 tbsp butter per bun pair - so 4 buns = 2 tbsp butter ya feel? Cook these in a large skillet set over medium-low. If they're brioche they tend to toast quickly, so I just wait for the butter to melt, pop the buns in, move them around to encourage even browning, and let them cook for about 1-2 minutes... usually the lower end of that. You want JUST golden. Remove and set aside. *I like salted butter here, but literally use anything you have. You can use oil if ya want!*
To assemble you top the bottom bun with 1/4 of the meat mixture, 1/4 cup shredded cheddar cheese, and pop that under the broiler for 1-3 minutes depending. You just want it melted.
Top with 3 pickles (or however many you want) and your top bum and BOOM! You're done.
ENJOY!!!!!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Cheeeesy Sloppy Joe!
Description:
I wanted to take that classic Sloppy Joe we all had as kids and make it with a super special sauce, shredded cheddar cheese cuz YUM, top it with picklez for a briney crunch, and of course pack it all in a buttery toasted brioche bun. It's sloppy, it's messy, it's perfect. 

I wanted this to be as easy as possible so we're using a WHOLE CAN of tomato paste instead of 1/2 a can plus ketchup plus tomato sauce like you'll traditionally see... so now you don't have to worry about wtf you're going to do with like 1/2 a can of tomato paste ya know? It's easy AND delish. My two favorite thingz.

You can use any cheese you have, but something about sharp cheddar just hits. Provolone or Swiss would also be banging!!

ingredients.Name: lemon juice, ACV, white wine or champagne vinegar
Optional:  tbsp finely chopped, fresh, soft herbs (parsley, basil, chives, etc)

directions.Direction: If you're just shaking it up I recommend adding it to a jar with a lid. If you're using a bullet blender, just do that lol. The blender WILL emulsify it better, but I get that sometimes a blender is just like a lot ya know...
Add ALL of the ingredients to your jar or blender bottle and mixie mix until combined. That's literally it.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: The Perfect Salad Dressing
Description:
I go to this salad dressing over and over and over. Sometimes I swap out lemon juice for ACV, but the core ingredients always remain the same. 

In the video I used up the last remaining, clinging to the sides of the jar, bits of mustard in my Lusty Monk Mustard jar. You can of course copy that thrifty hack ORRRR just use the correct quantity. You do you boo. 

Put it over salad, roasted veggies, as a dip. You name it !

ingredients.Name: medium sized sweet potatoes, skin removed and cooked

directions.Direction: Place the sweet potatoes in a bowl and mash up until no clumps remain. Word to the wise, if any chunks remain you WILL see it when you go to roll out the gnocchi.
Add the egg and mixie mix to combine.
Pour in 1 1/2 cups of all purpose flour and 1 tsp salt. Use your hands or a wooden spoon to mix until a dough begins to form.

Flour a clean work surface and dump out the sweet potato dough. Sprinkle with more flour and knead until a soft, but smooth and firm-ish dough forms. About 2 minutes. You will likely need to add flour to keep the dough from sticking to the counter and your hands, just try not to go past the 2 cups total amount.

Once you feel the dough is in a good place, pop it in a container or bowl and place in the fridge to firm up for about 20 minutes. (If you’re working in tandem with the chicken meatballs, start those while you’re waiting!)
Set a pot of heavily salted water over high heat to boil.

Once chilled, divide into 4 pieces. Working 1 portion at a time, roll out into a long strip/log until it is about 1 in thickness. Try your best to make the whole log the same thickness, but honestly it’s just homemade gnocchi it’s not that serious. Have fun with it.
Then use a ruler or your eyeballz and cut the log into 1 in pieces.
Use your hands or a bench scraper to toss the pieces in some flour to prevent sticking and add them to a bowl. Move on with the other 3 portions of dough.

Boil the gnocchi in 2-4 batches, all just depends on how big your pot is, and stir a little at the beginning to discourage sticking. Allow those to boil for 2-4, but once they rise to the top they’re done! Use a spider/strainer to remove and set aside while you boil the remaining batch(es).
Melt butter in a large skillet over medium heat and allow to brown slightly, about 4 minutes. You want it to smell toasty and sputter slightly.
Add in the sage, red pepper flakes, salt n’ pep and fry the sage for 1-2 minutes.
Add in the gnocchi and toss to coat.
If you’re making these with the chicken meatballs I like to add them in, cover the whole thing with parm, and toss to incorporate.
That’s it!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Sweet Potato Gnocchi N’ a Sage Brown Butter Sauce
Description:
I can’t even express how yummy and hearty these are. 

And best part? They are the PERFECT leftovers. They’re honestly even better the second time you heat them up. 
Just make sure to heat them in a skillet with some butter or ghee to get them a lil toasty. :) 

Make these with the Chicken Meatball recipe for a full on dinn dinn!

ingredients.Name: ghee, tallow, or oil of choice

directions.Direction: Heat oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat.

Once hot add in the ground bison. As always, make sure to evenly spread the bison out in the pan, but try to leave some space in between each piece so they brown instead of steam. Leave the bison undisturbed for 3-5 minutes on the first side to ensure that it properly browns/crisps. During that time sprinkle over the seasonings on top.
To see if the meat is properly browned, just flip over one piece and check it out. Pretty simple. If it’s deeply browned and crispy go ahead and flip everything else over. If not, keep cooking baby!
Once everything is cooked and flipped just break it up into teeny tiny lil bits, cook for another 1-3 minutes and remove once no more pink remains. Set aside.

You can totally just assemble from here, but if you want to go the extra mile just toast up the tortillas. I have a gas stove and just set it to medium-low and throw the tortilla right on top. You can also do a skillet and toast it for a minute on each side.
Then I evenly portion the remaining ingredients on top! I do meat, then cheese, then onion and cilantro, then avocado, some hot sauce, a squirt of lime and BOOM! YOU’RE DONE!
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Bison Tacoz!
Description:
These are perfect for when you want a legit, delicious dinner, but like really don’t feel like cooking. Ya feel me?

And plus you say “bison tacos” and just feel fancy. 👑

I already had some homemade flour tortillas so I used those, but use whatever kind you feel like. You don’t even have to reheat them, but I swear it takes like 2 seconds and makes them like 10 times better.

ingredients.Name: honey nut squash, peeled and seeds scooped
olive oil, plus more for drizzling

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 425F and prepare your squash.
Add squash, 4 sprigs of rosemary, and 9ish sprigs of thyme to a rimmed baking sheet. Drizzle olive oil allll over (you may need more)to coat the squash. Season with salt and pep.
Flip those babies on over so they're cut side down. Roast for 20 minutes, flip, and cook another 5-10 or until they are fork tender.

While that's cooking prep your coconut flakes. Just add the flakes and 1 sprig of thyme to a skillet over medium heat. Just toast for 3ish minutes or until they become fragrant and the edges slightly brown. Discard that rosemary and set coconut aside.
Use a bigggggg ol' platter and dump the whole 5oz container of yogurt on the bottom. Shhhhmear it around so it evenly covers your whole platter.
Top with the squash, pistachios, pomegranate, coconut, and the leaves of 1 sprig of thyme. Drizzle with honey (once again you may want more!!), more olive oil, and more salt n' pep.
You can absotootly eat this right away but I highly recommend eating it when cold! So prep this the day before and make your life easier on Thanksgiving day!
OR just cook this whenever because I legit eat this all Fall/Winter long.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: The Ideal HONEYNUT Squash
Description:
This honey nut squash really do be a party. 

My absolute favorite way to eat these hearty fall squash varieties is with a fattttt stack of plain greek yog. 
How to make it better? Top dat with pistachios, pomegranate seeds, toasty coconut flakes, olive oil, honey, N’ SALT doiiii.

THE BEST PART ABOUT THIS RECIPE is that it’s honestly most delicious when cold! So literally just make the platter the night before thanksgiving and BOOM you got yourself a delicious and nutritious side. 

Plus it’s like really fun and fancy and something new and special to add to your Thanksgiving spread.

ingredients.Name: Juice of  orange or 2 mandarine oranges
Zest of  orange or 2 mandarine oranges (2 tsp)

directions.Direction: Add cranberries to a sterile jar and mash until basically every single cranberry has been smooshed.
Add in remaining ingredients and stir to combine.
Close the lid of the jar and either burp daily OR close the clasp with a rubber band - this will ensure that any excess gas can push out and escape.
Let the jar sit in a room temp area out of direct sunlight for 2-7 days. I let mine go for 6 days, but my house is also pretty cold right now.
You should see some bubbling come to the surface when you open the jar. Also visually you should see that everything has softened blended together.
Once it is to your desired fermented level just pop it in the fridge until you’re ready to use it.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Fermented CRANBERRY SAUCE
Description:
t’s the cranberry sauce you know and love but with the added bonus of probiotics!!

This is the perfect swap to your canned cranberry sauce, but it’s also DELICIOUS as a spread on sandwiches, a punchy addition to drinks, or even as a dessert topping.

The best part? You don’t even need to cook anything!! You just pop it all in a jar and  let it do its thing.
Notes:
* Cook time is 5-10 minutes, basically just time to combine everything. Buttttttt it takes DAYS to ferment. Just keep that in mind!
* Raw honey is necessary here to facilitate fermentation.
* You can sterilize your jars by just washing them in the dishwasher. If you don't have a dishwasher you can either dunk them in boiling water OR wash with soap and HOT water.

ingredients.Name: Tteok Bok Ki (Trader Korean Joes Spicy Stir  Fried Rice Cakes)
carrots, sliced into lil baby matchsticks (basically as match sticky as you can, but don't lose your mind.)
oil, I used hump fat but you can use any kind you have
large chicken breasts, cut into chunks
coconut milk (if that's super annoying just add the whole thing and simmer longer. BUT it's the perfect amount for like morning oats or something)

directions.Direction: Heat about 1 tbsp oil in a large pan over medium high heat.

Once the oil is hot and shimmering, add in the chicken and sear on that first side for about 3 minutes. Season with salt n' pep. Flip one piece to test for browning, then if it's good flip everything over. Cook another 2-3 minutes on the other side(s), then remove and set aside. (It's ok if there's still a lil pink inside because it'll continue cooking later in the sauce.)
Add another tablespoon or so of oil, let that heat up, then add in the peppers and onions. Cook for about 5-7 minutes, stirring frequently. You want everything to soften!
Make some room in the center of the pan, add in the anchovy filets *(trust in the process)*, and stir those up until they sizzle fry and break down. Then stir into the pepper onion mixture.
Lower the heat to medium. Add the broccoli, carrots, garlic, and ginger. Cook another 3-5 minutes stirring frequently.
Add in the frozen rice cakes and sauce n' mixie mix to combine. Thennnnn add in the coconut milk and chicken. Mixie mix!!

Let this simmer on medium or medium-low for about 3-5 minutes. You want a gentttttle simmer. Stir frequently to make sure nothing is sticking to the bottom and burning. The sauce should thicken during this time.
While that's doing its final simmer chop up your peanuts if you haven't already!
Plate your stir fry in a coupe bowl, top with some peanuts, give it a lil squirt of lime juice and
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Spicy Coconut Rice CAKE Stir Fry
Description:
What you should probably make for dinner tonight 👏🏻

For real though, this WEEKNIGHT FRIENDLY meal brings nutrients, protein, ANNNND makes enough for you to still have leftovers to bring for lunch. 🔥

The most time consuming part is just cutting everything up, but once you have that down it goes quickly.

We go to max flavor town by we’re leaning on the bag of spicy frozen rice cakes from Trader Joes. The sauce is incredibly flavorful and just brings everything together. 
But I can’t just stop there so I added in coconut milk to make it a proper saucy sauce. 

PLUS you optimize time by not cooking rice… cuz ya got rice cakez. You’re welcome. 🎂

MAKE IT!

ingredients.Name: ground fennel seed (I ground mine in a spice grinder)
ground cloves (I ground 4 whole cloves in a spice grinder)
Zest from  large oranges, about 2 tsp
unsalted butter, cut into 4 chunks (feel free to sub with olive oil if you are dairy free)
Extra orange slices, cranberries, and/or rosemary for plating.

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 325F. Grab a 9x13 in baking dish with high walls (2 in) and plop your ham right on in there.
Mixie mix the sugar, salt, fennel, cloves, orange zest, and orange juice in a bowl.
Pour that mixture all over the ham, but no need to separate the slices of the ham. Just pour on the outside! In between the slices will soak up juice when we baste later!
Add butter and water to the bottom of the pan.

Pop dat in the oven and cook until the internal temp of the thickest part is 135-140F. Depending on the size of your ham that'll take anywhere from 1-2 hours. You can roughly account for 12 minutes per pound of meat.

During that time you will also be basting the ham every 30 minutes or so, so that could tack on some time too if your oven looses too much heat. All I do to baste is take a spoon, scoop up some liquid, and spoon it over. If you don't mind lifting it over and over I'd suggest removing it from the oven and closing the door while you baste it so you don't loose too much heat.
Once it reaches temp, place on another baking dish or bowl, cover with foil, and let rest for 20-30 minutes.
During that time we're going to reduce down that liquid mixture in the roasting pan. Just pour it into a pot and gently simmer until it has about halved in volume. Add in the ACV and dats it!
Place the ham on your serving platter, pour the sauce over the top, and garnish the platter with the additional orange, cranberries, or rosemary.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Orange and Brown Sugar Ham
Description:
This is THE ham you need to make this holiday season. 👏🏻
The orange and brown sugar bring sweetness, while the fennel and clove pack on some holiday flavor. 

It’s incredibly easy to make and a worthy centerpiece at your table!
Notes: * Check the salt level of your ham. If the ham is already heavily salted omit the salt in the spice mixture!!! However, if the ham somehow hasn't already been salted, then bump up the quantity from 1 tsp to 1 tbsp.

ingredients.Name: fresh rosemary finely chopped or 1/2 tsp dried rosemary (don’t fret if you don’t have this, it just lends a little aromatic flavor)
head of broccoli, chopped up into smallish pieces, nothing bigger than 1 inch
chopped, thick ham (leftover sliced ham is best)

directions.Direction: Heat ghee in a large dutch oven or pot over medium heat.
Cook onions and garlic for 3-5 minutes, until wilted and slightly browning
Add in rosemary and broccoli and cook for another 1-3 minutes, just to let those get a tinyyyyyy bit of wilting and color. Basically the broccoli will just become a more vibrant green.

Pour in the bone broth, peas, and ham. Cover with a tilted lid (to allow some steam to escape), lower the heat to medium-low and let simmer for 20 minutes. During this time the peas will soften.  I personally like mushy smushy peas, so I actually let mine go for closer to 30-40 minutes, but it’s totally up to you!
While the soup is simmering away idk, read a chapter of a book, do dishes, fold some laundry. This is YOU time so take it.
Once the peas are to your desired smushy level, just top with some freshly grated parm and
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: A Very Hammy Pea Soup
Description:
I love soup, my husband loves meat. So I bring you a Very Hammy Pea Soup. 

I ditch the classic constructs of a pea soup and opt for an f-ton of ham and boost that green color with some broccoli. 

Jam slam PACKED with nutrients.
We got some heart healthy nutrients in the peas, talking magnesium, potassium, and calcium. 
Fiber, vitamin K, iron, and moreeeee potass in the broccoli. 
MAJOR protein points in the max ham content. 
And plus extraaaaaaa protein and collagen in the homemade bone broth.
IT’S BEYOND. 

And also a great way to use up leftover ham! My Orange Brown Sugar ham is perfect here because it’s already loaded with flavor. 

It is super salty because of the ham, which I love, so just keep that in mind and DON’T salt your veggies. I know… it feels weird. 

It comes together FAST (then you simmer for a bit) and is totally weeknight friendly.
Notes: As I mention in the description, this soup can get pretty salty depending on how salty your ham and bone broth are. I personally love salt so this is my dream come true, but depending on your preferences you may want to just add some water to tone it down. It won't be as thick, but it'll be YOUR perfect salt level.

ingredients.Name: 8 oz boxes of Banza rotini (chickpea pasta)
fennel seeds (it's not the end of the world if you don't have fennel seeds)
grated parm (I like blender parm here!)
Lots o mozzarella cheeeeese! But really like  of a 16oz bag of mozzarella shredz
Salt n’ pep for seasoning PLUS to salt the pasta water

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 350F.
Set a large pot of heavily salted over high heat and bring to a boil.
Heat olive oil in a large (preferably oven proof) skillet over medium heat. Once hot and shimmery, add in the onions and mixie mix to coat in oil.
Add in the fennel and grated garlic (you can just grate right over the top of the skillet like I did). Mixie mix to combine. Cook for another 2-4 minutes or until the onion has softened.

Pour in the liquid from the can of tomatoes, then CAREFULLY just use your hand to mash up the tomatoes inside the can, then pour in. You can also just pour it all in and use a potato masher if you prefer.

Bring to a simmer and let that bubble away for about 15 minutes (should be about as long as it takes for your water to boil and noodles to cook) Season with salt and pepper to taste after it has reduced down.
While that’s simmering, once your water is boiling add in the pasta and cook it UNDER al dente. The box says 7-9 minutes so I did 6. It continues to cook in the oven and you don’t want it mushy!
Once the pasta is cooked, save 1 cup of pasta water JUST IN CASE and strain the rest.

I like to then pour the pasta back into the large pot, add the sauce, 1/2 of the parsley, and 1/2 of the parm. If the sauce reduced too much and it’s looking dry just add in 1/4 cup of that reserved pastas water at a time until you’re happy with it. You don’t want soupy, I’m just giving you a fallback if you walked away and the sauce reduced to nothin ya feel? Mixie mix that all up to combine.

Pour 1/2 of the pasta mix into that oven proof skillet we were just using (no need to clean it), top with several dollops of ricotta (you may use a little more or a little less ricotta depending on your preferences), and cover with a layer of mozzarella cheese. Pour the 2nd 1/2 of the pasta mix, coat with another layer of mozzarella.
Bake at 350F for 15 minutes, then broil for 1-4 minutes at the end to get some nice browning and bubbling on the cheese. DON'T WALK AWAY WHILE IT'S BROILING!
Sprinkle the remaining parm on top, then parsley. Allow to cool slightly before serving up.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: My VIRAL Easiest Baked Pasta UPGRADED
Description:
Y’all already know and loved my viral “easiest baked pasta” and guess what… it just got an UPGRADE! And just in time for the holidays!! 😎

The biggest upgrade was using Banza Rotini to pack on the protein in every 👏🏻single 👏🏻 bite 👏🏻. 

I come from an Italian family and we usually do an Italian menu for the holidays. So I wanted to build upon my already AMAAAAZING recipe and make it even more crowd friendly and a litttttttle fancier for the holiday spread!

It’s protein packed, vegetarian, creamy, cheesy, and soooo yummy! 

I make my own sauce here, but feel free to swap out and use 1 jar of premade sauce to make it even easier.

ingredients.Name: worth of finely diced baby portobello mushrooms (about 1/4 in cubes)
Japanese bbq sauce, I like original Bachan’s here
worth (or more if you just love toppings) of chopped pickled/fermented veg of choice (ideas in the description)
ish lettuce leaves, I love butter lettuce here but anything large enough to be a holding vessel will do. Even romaine would be fine!

directions.Direction: Heat 1 tbsp oil in a large skillet over medium heat.
Add in shallot, garlic, ginger, and mushrooms and cook for 2-3 minutes. You want them to soften but not totally frizzle and crisp up.
Push them over to one side of the pan and add the other 1 tbsp of oil.
Plop in your ground bison into chunks. I seasoned with salt and pepper but honestly, the sauces make it so salty and flavorful I’d skip it. But you do you!
Let those sear undisturbed for about 1 minute, then use a spoon or spatula to break the meat up into tiny bits.
Incorporate the shallot mixture and mixie mix everything to combine.
Add in the sauces, mixie mix, and lower the heat to medium-low.
Let that cook down for about 5 minutes or until the sauce thickens holds when you scrape your spoon against the pan. I show this in the video. Basically you just don’t want the sauce to be runny!
And that’s it!! Just assemble with a lettuce leaf, the meat mix, some pickled veg, and cilantro.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Bison Lettuce Wraps
Description:
TIME: 25 minutes ⏰
SERVINGS: 2 hungry adults 🧍🧍
DIETARY SPECS: High protein, Gluten-Free 💪🥬

It’s insane how much flavor we pack on in just 25 minutes! 
You’ll be sitting down enjoying a protein packed, delicious meal in no time. 😎

You know I love subbing ground Bison for Ground Beef to feel fancy. 👸🏼

And I reallllly didn’t want to make you use a bajillion different types of sauces and liquids to develop a sauce so we make it easy with some Bachans Original Japanese BBQ Sauce and Molasses. 

I topped mine with pickled radish, but that part is sorta a choose your own adventure thing. 🩷

Beef/bison wraps typically have pickled ginger on top, but I wanted to do something a little different (and I had these beaaaautiful pickled radishes from my local farmers market). 🫚

So use whatever pickled or fermented veg you have! It’ll all be deeeelicious!! 

Some options include:
✨Kimchi
✨Sauerkraut
✨Pickled ginger
✨Spicy pickles

ingredients.Name: Jasmin rice (or any kind you love)
chicken thighs, skin on bone in
lemons: 1 cut in half, 1 cut into 6 slices (ends removed)
finely chopped fresh rosemary, use 1 tsp if you’re using dried

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 425F
Rinse rice until the water runs clean. If you're not using jasmine rice you may have to alter the proportions.

Add 4 cups of bone broth to a medium sized pot, bring to a simmer, then add in rinsed rise. Lower temp to low or medium-low and cook until the moisture is absorbed and rice is soft. About 15 minutes. You can move onto the chicken while the rice is cooking!

Heat oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Once hot, add in shallots and garlic and cook for 1-3 minutes. You want softened and slightly frizzled. They should hit the pan and immediately start sizzling…. If they're not then you need to increase the temp. Season with salt and pep. Remove from the pan once cooked and set aside.

Add in all 6 chicken thighs, skin side down. The chicken will be sort of frying in all that oil! Increase the temp if the chicken/oil is not sizzling. Season that first side with salt and pepper. Let cook for about 5-7 minutes. You want the skin to get fairly browned and crispy. Flip, season the other side with salt, pep, AND rosemary. Cook for another 5-7 minutes.
Add 1/4 cup bone broth to the pan and juice of 1 lemon. Use a spoon to baste the chicken with the mixture.
Add the shallot mixture back in and top each chicken thigh with a slice of lemon. Baste the lemon slices as well.

Put in the preheated oven and cook for about 10-15 minutes, or until the internal temp reaches between 175-190. You want to go above the 165 safe temp so that the collagen and everything has extra time to break down. I cooked mine to 180-185 and they were outrageously juicy and moist!
Serve with a hefty portion of bone broth rice, 1 or 2 chicken thighs, and spoon over extra of those pan liquids!! I like to use some scissors to easily cut up some scallions right on top.
I am a salt maniac and LOVE a lil bit of flaky salt on top, but you do you. Also pro tip: smush the lemon slice to release all of those extra juices. It’s perfection.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Lemon Rosemary Chicken with Bone Broth Rice
Description:
TIME: 35 minutes ⏰
SERVINGS: 2  adults  +  Leftovers !🧍🧍
DIETARY SPECS: High protein, Immunity Boosting, Gluten Free 💪

THIS RECIPE IS PHENOMENAL! Seriously. So so so good and makes PERFECT leftover for lunch the next day. 

The rosemary and lemon combo is perfection 🍋👏🏻

And if you aren’t already cooking your rice in bone broth well… what are you doing? 
If gives you extra protein, collagen, and immune boosting benefits!

You gotta try this one!

ingredients.Name: large shrimps, peeled and deveined tail on is fine
bone broth (or water but you’ll need to account for salt at the end)

directions.Direction: Add 1 tbsp butter to a medium sized pot. Once melted add in both nuts and cook for 1-3 minute, stirring often, until fragrant and browning. Immediately move and set aside.

Add 2 tbsp butter to the same pot (no need to wash it) and sauté the onion until softened. Another 1-3 minutes should do. Then add in couscous and cook for 3-5 minutes, stirring frequently, until the couscous begins to brown and toast.
Pour in the bone broth, lower the temp to low, cover with a lid, and cook according to package instructions. Orrrr until the liquid is absorbed and couscous is soft - about 10 minutes.
While that’s cooking, let’s do the shrimp. Heat up a large skillet over medium-high heat and add olive oil and final 1 tbsp butter.

While the pan is heating up, combine shrimp, paprika, garlic powder, onion powder, cayenne, salt and pep. Once the pan is hot, add shrimp in a single layer (work in batches if you have to). Cook about 2-4 minutes on each side. It’s all going to depend on just how hot your pan is!! You want some serious sizzling on that shrimp!! Once cooked on each side, turn off the heat!
To finish off the couscous, add 2ish tbsp of the parsley (1/2 the amount), the toasted nuts, and raisins. Mixie mix to combine. Taste for salt level and adjust accordingly.
To plate, you add a hefty portion of the couscous, some shrimps, a sprinkle of parsley, and a squeeze of lemon juice.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Spicy Shrimp n’ Bone Broth Couscous
Description:
I am absolutely starving just staring at this Spicy Shrimp n’ Bone Broth Couscous. 🔥

The couscous gets some special treatment with parsley, toasty nuts, and raisins. Yes, I said raisins. 
They add such a wonderful sweetness to combat the spiciness of the shirmpz.

Plus, you know I will be replacing water with bone broth at just about any opportunity I get. 👏🏻

It’s incredibly easy to put together, totally weeknight friendly, and maybe your new favorite flavor combo. ❤️‍🔥

ingredients.Name: flank steak, cut into 1 x 2 x .5 in lil strips
medium yellow onion, cut into 1/4 in thick slices
worth of 1/2 in bell pepper slices
head of broccoli cut up plus remove the butter skin from the stem and cut into thick matchsticks
head of cauliflower, cut into 1/2 in strips (you want them about 2 x 2 x .5 in)
gochujang start low and add to your preferred spice level

directions.Direction: In a medium pot, bring bone broth to a boil. Once boiling, add in rice and cook until the liquid is absorbed and rice is tender.

Heat a large pan over medium-high heat and add in 2 tbsp ghee. Once rippin hot, add in beef and cook for about 2-4 minutes without disturbing it. During that time season with salt and pepper. Once the bottoms look like they’re browning just mixie mix dat all up and cook until very little pink remains. It’s ok if a little pink is left because it’ll continue cooking with everything else in a little bit. Remove from the pan and set aside.
Add the other 2 tbsp of ghee, melt dat, and then add in all of your chopped veg. Do your best to mixie mix dat all up. Lower the heat to medium and season with salt and pepper.
Stir frequently for about 10 minutes or until the vegetables are tender and starting to brown.

At that point add back in the beef plussss all the juices that end up in the bowl, 1/2 of the basil, the coconut aminos, gochujang, and orange juice. Mixie mix it all up and taste for seasoning. Adjust salt, pepper, and gochujang as needed.
Assemble by adding the bone broth rice to a bowl, then the stir fry, then additional basil.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Gochujang Beef Stir Fry n’ Bone Broth Rice
Description:
TIME:  30 ⏰
SERVINGS: 4 adults🧍🧍🧍🧍
DIETARY SPECS: High Protein, High Fiber, Immune Boosting
DAY: 5 / 100 🗓️

ALERT THE NEWS!! SHE USED BONE BROTH IN RICE! 🔥
Jk we all know by this point I will always replaced water with bone broth if I can. 

I know stir fry can be sorta blasé, but by adding gochujang we are really making it something special.
And as always I didn’t want you to have to use like a bajillion different sauces/spices in this to make it good, so we JUST HAVE THREE!  

You can mix and match with whatever vegetables you have on hand (or are looking sad in your fridge). 😘

ingredients.Name: olive oil, divided (some for drizzling on squash, some for cooking sausage, n' drizzle on the final product)
capers, (depends on how much you like capers 😉 )
grated parmesan cheese, plus more for plating
finely chopped parsley, reserve 1/2 for topping
Salt n' pep for seasoning, plus a ton of salt for pasta water

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 425F. Prep the squash by cutting it in half, scooping out the seeds, cutting into 1/2 inch half moons, then cut those into 1/2 inch chunks.
Add squash cubes to a sheet tray, drizzle with olive oil, salt, pep, and mixie mix. Roast for 20-25 minutes - until softened and browning.
Set a large pot of heavily salted water over high heat to boil. Once boiling add in the pasta and cook to al dente. Reserve 1 1/2 cups pasta water and set aside.

While the squash is cooking and water is boiling, heat a large skillet over medium heat and add 2 tbsp olive oil. Add sausage links and cook for about 3-5 minutes on each side (top, bottom, and both sides) - internal temp needs to read 160F. You may need to lower the heat a little about 1/2 way through cooking to prevent burning. Remove from the pan, allow to cool, and then chop at a bias into 1/2 inch rounds. (while the sausage is cooking you can grate your parm!)
Once the sausage is out, immediately add in the garlic, fry for literally like 30 seconds, then add in spinach and cook for 2-4 minutes, until totally wilted. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Add 1 cup of the reserved pasta water to that pan and plop in 1 tbsp of butter. Whisk constantly until the butter is melted and emulsified into the water. Continue working 1 tbsp of butter at at time until all of the butter has been incorporated. Add in the cheese and mixie mix until everything is incorporated.
Add in the pasta, mixie mix to coat. Taste test for seasoning and adjust salt and pepper accordingly.
Then add in sausage, spinach, squash, 1/2 the parsley, and capers.
Top with some parsley, a drizzle of olive oil, some flaky salt, extraaaaa parm, and some black pep.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Sausage, Spinach, n’ Squash Pasta
Description:
TIME:  40 ⏰
SERVINGS: 4 adults🧍🧍🧍🧍
DIETARY SPECS: Fuel for a heavy workout
DAY: 6 / 100 🗓️

This stunnnnning Sausage, Spinach, n’ Squash Pasta utilizes some in season delicata squash. 

This recipe sorta functions as a dance. You’re accomplishing tasks simultaneously so that by the end of it everything is ready to be thrown together and mixed up at the same time. 

It’s hearty, flavorful, n’ bright. And the best part is LEFTOVERZZZZ! Well, if you’re a family of 2 then you’ll have leftovers. 😉

ingredients.Name: oil (I prefer coconut oil for the flavor)

directions.Direction: Preheat air fryer to 400F

Let's prepare the dredging station. Grab 3 bowls and add cornmeal to 1, 2 eggs (mixed up) to another, and panko to the last one. Season all bowls with salt and pepper and the dry bowls with some garlic powder and paprika. No real measurements, but about 1/8-1/4 tsp.

Working one piece of chicken at a time, and using one hand at a time to keep one dry and one wet, coat the chicken tender in corn meal. Then plop into the egg and using your other hand coat in egg and allow the excess to drip off. Then plop in the panko and revert back to that dry hand and PRESS the chicken into the panko! I like to add some panko to the top of the piece so I have something dry to hold onto when I flip it to fully coat.
Repeat with all chicken tenders.
Liberally spray your air fryer basket liner and both sides of the chicken with oil. Once again I prefer coconut oil spray for the flavor.
"Fry" for a total of 10-12 minutes, flipping half way and respraying the top once flipped.
Check the internal temp and make sure it got to 165F!!

While that's cooking, combine the honey, mustard, and mayo for a quick n' easy honey mustard. You can also whip yourself up some broccoli or other veggies to make this a full meal. For the broccoli I just sautéed in some olive oil and seasoned with the garlic powder, chili powder, and salt and pep since they were already out.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: CRISPY AF Air Fryer Chicken Tenderz
Description:
Because it’s a new year and I want food that feels like it was fried but it ain’t!! 
Cuz health. 😎

These get some SERIOUS crunch because we're coating them in cornmeal and THEN panko!!
These are stupid crispy, stupid delicious, and stupid easy to make. I could honestly crush like 15 of them. 👏🏻
If you’re just making the chxxxx tendiez it takes a whopping 15 minutes. 

I whipped up some easy peasy broccoli and a HONEY MUSTARDDD to go along wit em. 
*which you can make while the chx is cookin, good lookin* 🔥

Eating healthy doesn’t need to be boring. 

MAKE THEM!

ingredients.Name: hard boiled eggs, sliced or chopped
small cucumber, sliced into 1/4 in rounds

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 425F. Grab a large baking sheet and place bacon on one half of the sheet, making sure to not overlap. On the other half of the sheet add the chicken. Drizzle on some olive oil, salt n' pep, and garlic powder. Use your hands to coat all the chicken and then spread out in a single layer.

Once the oven is preheated, add in the chicken and bacon. Cook for about 7-10 minutes, then flip both the bacon and chicken. Cook for another 7-10 minutes and the bacon should be fully cooked and crispy. Keep an eye on it as the thickness of the bacon will determine how long it takes to cook. ANNNND if it's thin it can go from floppy to burnt real quick. Remove the bacon and continue cooking the chicken. The chicken will take another 5-7 minutes, but if you want max golden brown you can pop it under the broiler for a couple minutes too. Remove chicken once browned and internal temp is 165F.
To assemble the salad just do romaine, then top with eggs, cucumber, cornichon, tomato, and avocado. You can make it as pretty as you want but it's just gonna get covered so you do you.
Prep the ranch dressing. Literally just combine everything in a bowl or mason jar and mixie mix. I like a mason jar because I can just put the lid on it and shake!

Once the chicken and bacon are cooked and slightly cooled, chop the bacon into BITZ and chicken into chunkz. Top the salad with the chicken and bacon, then pour over your ranch dressing. Mixie mix the salad to combine and
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: a Cobb-ish Salad
Description:
Listen, I’m not really a salad girlie. For that matter, I’m not really an anything raw girlie. 
I like warm cooked things that make my tummy feel like it just got a hug, ya know? 🤗

But! THIS SALAD. THIISSSSSS salad!!!!! Somehow this salad doesn’t really feel RAW. 
Likely because the chicken and bacon get thrown in warm which is glorious, don’t question it. 

It’s got the bonez of a Cobb but like at the end of the movie when she takes her lettucey glasses off and suddenly she’s hot. 🔥
*no hate to glasses I love my glasses*

The super bright and briny cornichons reallllly do a lot here!

I mean… homemade ranch. HOT. nuff said. 

And don’t get it twisted. I do love a good sal lad sometimez. But this one… this I could eat ALL THE TIME. 
Likely because it has eggs, bacon, chicken, and greek yog and you know your girl loves her some protein. 🥓🐓

ingredients.Name: 6in tortillas (ideally homemade sourdough tortillas but I’m not gonna judge ya)
small salmon filets, skin off (about 1 lb), cut into 1 in cubez
shredded cabbage (I used the 9oz bag of organic shredded green and red cabbage with orange carrots from Trader Joes)

directions.Direction: Preheat air fryer or oven to 350F. Coat either your frier basket or a baking sheet with olive oil to prevent the salmon from sticking. Set aside.
Combine salmon, dry seasonings, olive oil, maple syrup, and salt and pep in a bowl. Mixie mix to make sure everything is evenly coated. Pour onto your oiled/prepared baking sheet/basket.
Fry for 8-10 minutes or bake for 10-12 minutes.
While that’s cooking throw together your slaw. Just combine the cabbage, yogurt, mayo, lime, and some more salt n’ pep. Mixie mix to totally coat everything.
If you made your tortillas that day you can just move on, but if you didn’t you may want to warm them up on a pan or directly on an oven flame (carefully)
I like to evenly distribute all of the salmon among the tortillas, then top each one with cabbage, cilantro, lime juice, and hot sauce. But you do you.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Air Fried Salmon Tacos
Description:
Made these beauties with HOMEMADE Sourdough Tortillas, Air Fried Salmonnnn, n’ a super quick yog slaw.

And TBH if you don’t make the tortillas yourself you could whip this up in like 15 minutes which I consider I MAJOR win for how f-ing delish these were. 

Sourdough Tortilla Recipe below:

https://www.southyourmouth.com/2023/03/baked-bang-bang-salmon-bites.html

ingredients.Name: parsley (about a handful of leaves and stems)
1/3ish cup olive oil (you may need more)
You can add  tbsp water if it really isn't blending...
low moisture, whole milk mozzarella, 1/2 cut into 1 in cubez and the other 1/2 cut into 1/4 in cubez
bone broth, water, or a combo of the two

directions.Direction: Preheat the oven to 400F

Letz make the pesto! Grab either a food processor, blender bullet, or mortar and pestle. Add in the parsley, spinach, onion, pine nuts, garlic, and olive oil. Blend until smooth (you may need to add some extra oil to get it to move).
Add the parm, salt n' pepper, and mixie mix again just to combine. Once again if it doesn't move you can add some water, but LESS IS MORE!

Grab a large casserole dish. Plop the Boursin Cheese right in the center, then pour the penne around it, top with the 1/2 in cube mozzarellaz, the peas, and bone broth/water. If any pasta is sticking up try to just smoosh it down, it's not that serious if some is poking out.
Cover with aluminum foil and bake at 400F for 20 minutes.

After 20 minutes remove the foil, and use a wooden spoon to mix everything up. The Boursin should be nice and melty and cheese very cheesy. At this point it'll look like a lot of liquid is left and that's ok.

Add the 1/4 in cube mozzarellazzz and the extra grated parm on top. Pop back in the oven for 25-35 minutes. You want the sauce super bubbly and cheese browning on top. If you want to take the browning on top even farther just set the oven to broil for the last 1-3 minutes.
Let rest for AT LEAST 5 minutes, but ideally like 10-15. Honestly, the leftovers are the BEST so you could even make this ahead and heat up the next day.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: No Boil Baked Pesto n’ Pea Penne PASTAAA
Description:
This pasta is BONKERZ. Like we don’t even need to boil the noodz first and that’s a BIG thank you to @banza for dat one. 

The only prep you have to do is make the pesto which, let’s be honest the mixer basically does that for you. 

Ya just throw everything together in a large baking dish (yes, EVEN THE DRY NOODLEZ) and BOOM you have a deeeeelicious dinner that hides a BUNCH of vegetables inside for you. And who would even know when you have all dat ooey gooey cheeeeeese?!

And before you say anything, this pasta has TONZ of protein thanks to the chickpea penne that we use 🔥 

It’s creamy. It’s cheesy. It’s pesto-y. It’s FANTASTIC.

ingredients.Name: Noodz of choice, but I vote linguine, bucatini, or spaghetti
ish in knob of ginger, finely chopped

directions.Direction: Boil some heavily salted water and cook pasta to al dente, reserving 1 cup of pasta water.
Add shrimp to a large bowl and pat dry. Add in chili powder, some salt n’ pep, and mixie mix to coat everything.

Add some oil to a big ol’ pan, heat to medium-high. Once shimmering, add in the shrimps (you’ll likely have to cook in batches, adding some oil each time). Cook for 2-3 minutes on each side, or until nice and browned. Remove and set aside.
Next more oil and throw in your garlic and ginger. Let those toasty-toast for a minute. BUT SERIOUSLY just like 30-60 seconds while you’re moving it around. We don’t want that to burn.
Then add in gochujang and tomato paste and cook until the tomato paste goes from bright red to like a more brick red. That’ll take about 30-90 seconds while moving constantly.
Add rice wine vinegar, mixie mix.
And last but certainly not least, add in your heavy cream. Depending on the gochujang you use you may need to add more or less to adjust to your desired spice level. You do you.
Add the cooked noodz straight to the pan and toss them, twirl them, spin them, smother them in the sauce. Add 1/4 cup water at a time to thin it out.
Plate dat pasta up, top with skrimpz, and some green onions for garnish.
ENJOY 🔥

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Spicy Shrimp n' Gochugang PASTA
Description:
Yes, the shrimp is spicy and YES gochugang is obvvvvvvvs spicy but! 
As a self proclaimed "spice weenie" I DEVOUR this! 😮‍💨

The creaminess of the sauce helps tame some of the spice, but like it's still very much there and ALLLLL the flavors are just popping. 

I did a littttttle bit of an update on the recipe that Jake Goldberg and I made.

This comes together really fast (I mean shrimpz cook in the blink of an eye) and you'll FOR SURE have leftovies.

MAKE THIS 🔥

ingredients.Name: bone in, skin on chicken thighs
Salt for seasoning the cilantro sauce

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 400F.
If you want the crispiest chicken skin you can get, pat the chicken dry. If you want still crispy chicken skin and want to be a little less fussy, don’t even bother.
Smother the chicken in the olive oil and spices until evenly coated.

Place on a rimmed baking sheet and bake at 400F for 30-40 minutes. Chicken is fully cooked when the internal temp reaches 165F, but you want to take chicken thighs a little farther to help them get tender. I try to shoot for somewhere around 185-190F. *if you don't have an instant read thermometer just go until the chicken is deeply browned and crispy!*
While the chicken is baking throw together your cilantro sauce. IT’S SO EASY.

If you don't have a blender: Super finely chop the cilantro, mash the feta, and mix in the yogurt. 1. This will take extra time and 2. It’ll be chunkier, which honestly may not be a bad thing. *taste and adjust for salt*
If you do have a blender: Just pop the cilantro, yogurt, feta, and a little salt in a blender and blitz dat up. *taste and adjust for salt*
I like to be a total animal and just dip and eat the chicken with my hands, but I mean you could be civilized and use a fork and knife. However you decide to eat it,
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: PERFECTLY Spiced Chicken Thighs n’ Cilantro Feta Sauce
Description:
This entire recipe is SO EASY!! The prep time is minimal and you have like 3 dishes to clean up!

I’m not kidding that when I ate this for the first time I audibly said “holy $hit” 🔥

I’ve been pretty obsessed with this spice combo on chicken lately and it just hits EVERY TIME. ❤️‍🔥

I typically make the cilantro sauce with just yogurt n’ salt, which… is DELISH but it just wasn’t the texture I was going for. 
So cue, FETA! 😮‍💨

And dear god I’m so happy that I added it in because it’s seriouslyyyyy doing somethings special wit deez PERFECTLY spiced chicken thighs. 

You could eat this alongside some bone broth rice, veg, or even (my choice) tostones!

ingredients.Name: Slider rolls (I went with the Bakerly brand that has  slider buns)
Thinly sliced red onion for topping the sliders
or more bbq sauce (I used Bachan's Hot and Spicy)

directions.Direction: If you're not smoking your meat, just skip ahead to step 6 :)
To smoke your meat, preheat smoker to 225F.

While that's preheating season your chuck with some salt, pepper, and garlic powder all over. You can do this the night before if you remember, but immediately before you cook it won't hurt anything. Place directly on the smoker grill plate and cook for about 2-3 hours (2 hours for a smaller cut, 3 hours for larger). During that time you'll baste it every hour with a total of 1 cup of broth.

Take the remaining 2 cups of broth and add it to a pan along with the yellow onion slices. Put the meat on top and increase the temperature to 250F. Cook for an additional 1-3 hours, or until it hits 165F. My beef was on the smaller end and cooked REALLY fast.

Cover with foil and let that continue to cook until it reaches 200F OR until it starts to shred easily. Once again my cut was on the smaller end so it reached temp QUICKLY, but it was still pretty tough. So I just kept cooking it until it was tender. About 2-3 hours total while covered.
Once easily or relatively easy to shred apart, SHRED IT! Then add in about 1/4 cup bbq sauce of choice and mixie mix it all up.
Cut your buns in half if they aren't already and toast both of the cut sides in a buttered pan. I personally like to assemble in one big "tray" and then pull apart.

Add ALL of your beef to the bottom layer of buns, top each slider section with 2-3 pickles, and the whole thing with sliced red onion. Add the mayo amount of your choice to the top buns. Then top the sliders with the top buns and that's it!
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Smoked Chuck Sliders
Description:
PLEASE don't let the "smoked" piece of this scare you. At the end of the day they're just some shredded chuck sliders. So if that means you need to bake the chuck, throw it in the crock pot, or heck even get some from your favorite BBQ shop, you can still make these. 

They're outrageously easy to throw together once you have the meat cooked. 

Recipe for smoked chuck adapted from HeyGrillHey
Notes: I know the wide time windows may be annoying, but smoking meat is sort of like baking. The exact temperature of your smoker, size of your meat, and positioning IN the smoker all contribute to how the meat cooks. And those are just a few of the factors!! PLEASE ask your questions below and I'll do my best to answer <3

ingredients.Name: sweet onions, skin removed and quartered

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 335F. Prep meat by liberally seasoning all surface areas of the meat with salt and pepper. If you have boneless, season the inside meat as well and then form back into a roast like shape.

Prep a roasting pan with all of the onions, garlic, and rosemary. Drizzle with olive oil, and sprinkle with salt and pepper. Place the roast on the bed of produce and pour in the bone broth around the pan. Drizzle some olive oil on the roast as well.
Cover with aluminum foil and bake for 2 hours. After the 2 hours remove the foil and continue baking for 2-3 more hours - until deeply browned and shredding easily.
To make the gravy: strain the pan juices into a pot, add the water, and bring it to a boil. Lower the temp to medium/high.
SLOWLY whisk in the all purpose flour, only adding about 1-2 tablespoons at a time, whisking until completely incorporated before adding more.

Once ~gravy thickness~ add in the salt, maple syrup, and apple cider vinegar. Taste for seasoning and adjust accordingly. If you want it outrageously smooth strain it one more time to remove any potential flour clumps.
Plate the shredded lamb with the warm gravy.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Boneless Leg of Lamb
Description:
What's an Easter dinner without lamb as the centerpiece?

I know lamb can seem a little intimidating, but it's truly so easy to make if you have some time and patience. We cook this low and slow until it's outrageously tender. 

The prep work is minimal before baking, then you get a 4-5 hour break to focus on other things like showering, reading a book, or yeah maybe just making a bunch of other sides…

But it is so tender, shreddable, and finger licking good with the gravy.

ingredients.Name: grated gruyere or sharp cheddar cheese

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 400F.

Begin with one layer of potatoes on the bottom of the skillet. Season with salt and pepper, and add about 1/2 of the grated cheese. Repeat until you use all of the potatoes, but DO NOT add a final layer of cheese.
Dot the top with the 4 tbsp of butter cubes and pour in the 2 cups of heavy cream.
Place on the stove and bring to a boil. Immediately reduce the heat to low (be careful to not let it boil over!) and simmer for 10 minutes.
Place in the oven on a rimmed baking sheet and immediately lower the temp to 350F. Bake for 20 minutes or until the top is golden brown.
Remove and top with the remaining 1/2 of the cheese. Return to the oven to bake for another 5-10 minutes or until the cheese is melted and golden.
Sprinkle the top with some nutmeg and your fresh thyme leaves. Let rest for 5-10 minutes before cutting into it.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Skillet Potatoes Au Gratin
Description:
Looking for a ridiculously easy and delicious side dish? Then seriously, look no further because this is it. 

These are so easy to prep and then the oven does the rest! The skillet is the perfect way to take a bake directly from the oven to the table. Because let's be honest, skillets are kinda chic. 

It's super cheesy, creamy, and the perfect tender yet toothsome bite of potatoes.

ingredients.Name: bone in skin on chicken thighs
chicken broth, plus more for bone broth rice
sliced green olives, Castelvetrano is preferred

directions.Direction: Preheat the oven to 350F.
Add olive oil to a large, high walled, oven proof skillet and heat to medium-high.

Season chicken with salt and pepper on both sides and add to the hot oil. Cook skin side down first for 5-7 minutes, until the skin is deeply golden and crispy. Cook on the other side for about 5 more minutes, then remove and set aside.
Add onions and garlic and cook, stirring frequently, until softened and starting to brown. About 5-7 minutes.
Add anchovy filets and tomato paste and cook until the anchovy is fully broken down and tomato paste goes from bright red to burnt red. About 2-3 minutes.
Add in wine and broth and let simmer until the alcohol smell goes away. About 3-5 minutes. During this time use your spoon to scrape up any browned bits on the bottom of the pan.
Lower the heat to low and add in heavy cream. Mixie mix to combine.
Add the sun dried tomatoes, olives, parm, and basil leaves. Mixie mix to combine.
Place the chicken back in the pan, skin side up, and pour in any juices left in the bowl/plate.
Add the entire skillet to the oven and bake for another 15-25 minutes, until the internal temp of the chicken is 180-190F. Taste test the sauce and season with salt and pepper accordingly.

While the chicken is baking make some bone broth rice! Just use the remaining broth you have and whatever rice you have on hand. Cook to your rice's specific ratios, but please make sure to rinse your rice first! It makes such a better batch I swear.
Serve chicken over the bone broth rice with plenty of the sauce.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Marry Me Chicken's Chic Older Sister
Description:
I had this intense craving for a tomatoey creamy chicken and then realized well wow, that’s basically just Marry Me Chicken. But this one is like 10000 times better. 

A solid 10/10 dinner and you can even add extra chicken thighs to give yourself some leftovies. 

I personally like to eat this with bone broth rice, but make whatever carb you think sounds best!

ingredients.Name: little gems lettuce (romaine or butter work well too)
cucumber, sliced into half moons and smashed if you're into that
Extra dill (you'll use it in the ranch too) for topping
Salt and pep for seasoning the steak

directions.Direction: If you have the wherewithal to remember to season your steak a couple hours before that's great!! If not, don't worry about it. Either way, liberally season both sides of the steaks with salt and pepper.

Heat a heavy bottomed or cast iron skillet over medium-high heat. Add in some oil and plop in the steaks. To achieve medium-rare I cook mine on the first side for about 4-6 minutes, flip, and then remove when it reaches 125F (another 4-6 minutes). For medium let it go to 135F. This should give you a steak with a crusty crust and a tender center. Remove and set aside.
While the steak is cooking (or before) prep and cut the avocado, tomatoes, and cucumber. Cut the steak into slices once it has rested for about 10 minutes.
Assemble the salad on either a platter or in a bowl, but I'm team platter. Top with some extra fresh dill!
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Steaky Ranch Salad
Description:
It’s a Steaky Ranch Salad and we all need it. 

Sometimes the craving just hits for a hearty and protein packed salad and when it does, I loveeeee to make one of these. 

The 2 non-negotiables for me are 1. a great crust on the steak and 2. making your own flippin ranch. 

It’s so easy to make ranch and is like 1,000 times better, better for you, and better for your wallet. 
So just do yourself a favor and stop buying it at the store plzzzzz.

I mean, I personally think all the toppings are essential too, but you get my gist.

ingredients.Name: sesame oil (toasted or un toasted is fine)
shaved beef steak (I got mine at Trader Joes, but you can just ask the butcher to do it too)
small heads of broccoli, florets separated from the stem
sprigs of green onion cut on a bias

directions.Direction: First start on your rice. I personally like jasmine rice here, but use any rice that you have and cook it according to the package instructions. However, please make sure you rinse your rice until the water running through is clear! For jasmine I rinse and do 2 cups water to 1 cup rice. You can also double this quantity if you love rice and/or want to stretch this meal farther.

Make your sauce. You're going to combine the soy sauce, ginger, garlic, maple syrup, molasses, sesame oil, and vinegar. Then add in the corn starch and whisk to combine. Slowly add in the hot water while whisking to further break down the corn starch and help it incorporate. Taste it and add some black pepper if you think it needs it. Set this aside for now.

Heat 2-3 tbsp olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add in onions and broccoli, season with some salt and pep, and cook for about 5 minutes. You want to stir it frequently during this stage so that evenly gets evenly softened. Then let it cook undisturbed for another 2-3 minutes to get the veg a little bit browned/charred. Remove and set aside.

Add another 1-2 tbsp of olive oil to the pan and increase the temp to medium-high. Add in the shaved beef and let cook undisturbed for about 2-3 minutes. You want that initial layer to get browned, because browning is flavor!! Then use a spoon or spatula to stir it all around until most of the beef is cooked, but some of the pieces are still a little pink.

Add the broccoli and onions back to the pan and mix to combine. Then add in the sauce mixture and lower the temp to medium-low. Stir until the sauce has thickened to your desired consistency; about 2-3 minutes.
Assemble with some white rice, the beef and broccoli mixture, and any toppings you like! I did green onions in the video, but sesame seeds and chili crisp are also wonderful additions!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Not Boring Beef n’ Broccoli 🥦
Description:
Not only is it totally not boring, but we don’t use any refined sugar making this good and good for you. 
I mean hello, PROTEIN. 🤌🏻

Plusssss we pack on some immune boosting ginger and garlic cause HEALTH. ✨

This is your “Better Than Takeout” weeknight friendly new dinner bestie, ok?

ingredients.Name: Fettuccini Noodles (homemade LINKED or store bought)

directions.Direction: DIRECTIONS FOR GIN SAUCE:

Heat olive oil in a high walled skillet over medium heat. Add in onion and garlic and cook for 5-7 minutes stirring frequently. You want the onion to soften and then get a littttttle browned and frizzly. Cuz browning is flavor.
Add in the tomato paste and cook for 2-3 minutes, letting the paste go from bright red to brick red.
Add in the gin and either be insane like me and flambé that... or just be normal and let it cook down until all of the liquid has been evaporated.
Use your hands to carefully smoosh the peeled tomatoes and break them down. You can also do this in a pan with a potato masher. Dump the tomatoes into the skillet and stir to combine.
Plop in the fresh basil and let the sauce simmer on medium-low for 20ish minutes. Pour in the heavy cream and stir to combine. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

While you're cooking the sauce, boil your noodles. Cook to just under al dente and take the fettuccini directly from the pasta water to the sauce. It's great if some pasta water comes along with the noodles! You may even want to add extra pasta water to thin out the sauce if it cooked down too much.
Continue cooking and stirring the noodles in the sauce for optimal flavor!
FOR THE BLACKENED CHICKEN:
Heat olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat.
While that's heating season the chicken. Basically I just sprinkle salt, pepper, onion, and garlic powder over the chicken on both sides. No real measurement, just a sprinkle.

Place chicken in the skillet and cook on the first side, undisturbed, for about 5-7 minutes or until deeply browned and almost blackened. Flip and repeat. Use a kitchen thermometer to temp it and continue cooking, flipping as needed, until the internal temp is 165F.
FOR ASSEMBLY:
To assemble I do noodles, sliced chicken, pesto, extra flaky salt, and parm on top! Daniel loves it with some red pepper flakes :)
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Fettuccine Alla Gin > Vodka
Description:
MAMA MIAAA! 
Move over fettuccini alla vodka, we have a new bestie in town and her name is GIN. 

Sure you can use vodka, but that's boring. This is everything you LIVE LAUGH LOVE about the tradish version, but like way cooler cuz gin. 

So basically the stand alone recipe here is the GIN SAUCE, but I paired this with my homemade fettuccini, pesto sauce, and blackened chicken. I'll be tagging the fettuccini and pesto recipes below and will outline how I made the blackened chicken.

ingredients.Name: Juice of  lime (save the other half for plating!)

directions.Direction: Let's start with marinating the shrimp! To a bowl add the shrimp, orange juice, lime juice, garlic, maple syrup, olive oil, and some salt and pep. Pop that in the fridge while you prep everything else.
Turn your grill on and let that preheat. You can also do this in a pan and completely omit the kebab sticks!
Chop the zucchini, onion, and bell pepper into bite sized chunks. You want them big enough to withhold a kebab stick being shoved into them.

Prep the Baja Sauce by combining the yogurt, mayo, lime juice, smoked paprika, cajun seasoning, cilantro and hot sauce. I only do a couple drops of hot sauce since I'm a spice weenie. Let that chill in the fridge. All of the flavors will continue to come together as it rests!

Cook the bone broth rice according to whatever your specific rice instructions are. I typically use organic jasmine rice and know that it is a 2:1 ratio. I rinse the rice (a step that is necessary no matter what kind of rice you use), then add it to a pot of boiling bone broth, stir it around, turn the heat to low, cover, and let it cook! Since each rice is different just time it according to your needs.
Assemble the kebabs by adding the marinated shrimp, zucchini, onion, and bell pepper to the kebab stick in any order that makes you happy. You can add other veggies here too!!

Grill for several minutes on each side or until the shrimp are opaque and fully cooked and veggies are soft and browning. I like to spoon the leftover marinade over the kebabs as they cook. Each grill is going to be different so adjust accordingly. Move the kebabs around as you grill so you don't char any spot too heavily.
You can also do this in a pan and don't even need to use the kebab sticks! Just add everything to a large skillet and cook in some oil until the shrimp are cooked and veggies are tender.

I plate everything by removing the goodies from the kebabs, yes... all that work just to remove them, and then eat with some of the rice and baja sauce. Top with extra cilantro, lime juice, and a spicy pepper on the side if you're into that.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Marinated Shrimp Kebabs with Baja Sauce
Description:
Some recipes just hit, this is one of them!

The shrimp get marinated in a citrusy sauce (but not for too long because we're not going for ceviche here...) and then cooked on the grill with some veggies. The two things that really bring this together are the Baja Sauce and Bone Broth Rice. 

This recipe was SO GOOD I literally made it two nights in a row. I'm honestly craving it again now...

ingredients.Name: zucchini, chopped into 1/2 in half moons
bell peppers, sliced into 1/2 in strips
red onion, sliced into 1/4 in strips
fresh oregano finely chopped or 1 tsp dried
ground beef (I used a beef organ mix)
shredded cheddar cheese (I used Raw Farm Usa Jalapeño Cheddar)

directions.Direction: Heat 1 tbsp oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the beef in dollops - essentially trying to get it spread evenly across the pan with some space between the pieces so they brown instead of steam. Season with salt and pepper and let cook undisturbed for 3-5 minutes - until pretty darn browned!
Break up the beef and continue to cook for a couple more minutes - until little or no pink remains. Remove the beef from the pan and set aside.

Add the onions, peppers, zucchini, and garlic to the pan and toss in the fat. Season lightly with salt and pepper. Let cook until the onions and peppers are softened and zucchini is browning in spots - about 5-7 minutes. Stir frequently.
Add in the boc choy and oregano and toss until wilted.
Add the enchilada sauce, mixie mix, and let simmer for a couple minutes to thicken.
Add in the cheese and mixie mix to melt and combine.
Serve with tortillas, cilantro, lime, and/or avocado!
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Fajita Enchilada Skillet
Description:
Don't think too much about the name, just go with it. 

It's everything I want in fajitas and enchiladas, but without actually having to turn on the oven. Once everything is chopped it only takes 20 minutes to throw this together and makes fantastic leftovers!

ingredients.Name: packs Cold Cracked Lobster from Butcherbox thawed
thinly sliced chives, plus more for topping
Lettuce leaves  ideally butter, gem, or something crisp
butter, plus 1/2 tbsp for browning the buns

directions.Direction: Heat 2 tbsp butter in a skillet over medium high heat. Add the thawed lobster and cook for about 5-7 minutes, stirring frequently, until opaque and the internal temp registers about 135-140F. Remove and let cool.
To a bowl add the mayo, lemon juice, lemon zest, celery, and 1 tbsp chives. Give that a lil mixie mix and season with a little salt and pepper.
I like to separate the large chunks of lobster meat and then chop the smaller bits up. I think it provides a good juxtaposition of texture in the filling.
Toss the lobster meat in the mayo mix and mixie mix dat up. Taste again and adjust with salt and pepper accordingly. Remember that the bun will overpower some of the flavor.
You can either leave this mixture out while you toast the buns or place in the fridge and let cool completely. Warm will be more Connecticut, cold will be more Maine.

Add the remaining 1/2 tbsp butter to a pan and heat over medium heat. Toast the buns on all 3 sides except the top. The buns usually toast pretty darn fast so keep an eye on it! It may only be like 30 seconds a side depending on how hot your pan gets. It could also take about 1-2 minutes on each side... so just go off of visual versus time.
Add a couple of lettuce leaves to the inside of the bun, then top with half of the filling, and extra chives and maybe even some flaky salt.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: THE Lobster Roll
Description:

directions.Direction: Start by heating 1/4 cup olive oil in a large oven-proof skillet over medium heat. Once shimmering add in the chicken breast - do this in batches if you can't fit all 6 in a single layer. Season the exposed side with salt and pepper. Let that cook until golden brown on the first side, about 5-7 minutes. Flip, season again with salt and pep, and let cook for another 5-7 minutes. You don't need the chicken fully cooked at this point (it won't be...) Set aside in a bowl.

***I recommend cutting everything else up while the chicken is cooking! Work smarter not harder. That means slice the onion, garlic, chop the capers, and parsley. Zest the lemon, THENNNN thinly slice half of the lemon to get 6 pieces, and save the other half for juicing. Remove the seeds from the 6 lemon slices.

Add the extra 1 tbsp olive oil to the pan with all of the chicken bits. Add in the onions and sauté until softened and starting to frizzle, about 5-7 minutes. Season with salt and pep. Stir frequently so nothing chars.
Add the anchovy filets and let those fry and naturally break up when you stir them around. Any anchovy haters, don't worry you won't even be able to "taste" them.

Add the garlic, capers, 1 tbsp parsley, lemon zest, and 1/4 cup white wine. Lower the heat to medium-low and use your spatula to mix and scrape any leftover browned bits off of the bottom of the pan. Let that simmer away until the alcohol boils off and liquid reduces.
Add in the 1/2 cup bone broth and working 1 tbsp at a time, add in the butter. You want to whisk between each addition to encourage the sauce to emulsify.
Add in the bag of spinach and mix until wilted. Taste the sauce for flavor here. You will likely need to add more salt, but it all depends on how salty your bone broth was!

Add the 6 chicken breast back to the pan, top each with a lemon slice, and spoon over some of the sauce. Increase the temp to medium and let the chicken cook in the pan for 5-7 minutes, or until the internal temp reaches about 150F.

Pop that under the broiler (ideally the lower or middle of the oven) and broil until the sauce is bubbly and lemon is slightly charred, and the internal temp of the chicken is 165F. You may have to add extra water to bring the sauce back together.
Squeeze the leftover 1/2 lemon over all of the chicken, sprinkle on the last 1 tbsp parsley, and top with some flaky salt.
Eat with pasta, rice, cous cous, or on it's own!
ENJOY!

ingredients.Name: Sir Kensingtons Avocado Oil Mayo for toasting the buns and slathering on as a topping

directions.Direction: If you can dry rub your chicken the night before that's fantastic! If not, just do it first and then prep everything else. So combine the salt, brown sugar, and black pep, then spread evenly over the four chicken thighs. Let those hang out in the fridge until you're ready to move on.

Set up your dredging station: get a wire wrack or plate and two large bowls. Add flour, corn starch, and spices to one bowl. Then add the wet ingredients to another. Whisk both individually to combine the contents of each bowl.

Working one piece of chicken at a time, plop the chicken thigh into the dry mixture and flip until fully coated (using one hand). Then shake off the excess and place it back on the wire rack. Repeat with the remaining 3 chicken thighs.

Then take 2-3 tbsp of the milk mixture and add it to the dry bowl. Mix that! Basically this is adding textural bits to the breading. Then plop the chicken in the milk mixture (using the other hand), shake off the excess, and plop into the dry mix. Coat the chicken one more time in the dry mixture making sure to press it into the chicken. Repeat with the three remaining pieces, placing them back on the wire rack once coated.
Place in the fridge while we clean up and heat up the oil.

Add enough tallow (or other oil) to a heavy bottomed skillet (I like cast iron) to come up about 1/2 inch. We're not deep frying here! Once that reaches 350F you are ready to add your chicken. If you do not have a thermometer you can just take a tiny bit of the breading and plop it into the oil, you want a moderate sizzle.

You will likely had to work in 2 batches, but add the chicken thighs to the pan and let fry on that first side for about 3-5 minutes, flip, another 3-5, and just keep flipping until the sides are evenly browned and golden (and temp is 165F or higher). You will likely have to keep a close eye on the temperature setting of the stove, adjusting as it needs more or less heat. Immediately place on a wire rack to drain.

Lightly coat the inside of each bun with some Sir Kensingtons Avocado Oil mayo. Toast the buns, mayo side down, in a skillet over medium-low heat. Move them around to encourage even browning and keep a close eye on them! If your pan is properly hot they should toast in just about 60 seconds or less!

Last but not least assemble your shredduce-y slaw! We do this last so it doesn't get soggy. Combine vinegar, Sir Kensingtons Avocado Oil Mayo, sugar, salt, and pepper. Then add in the lettuce and toss to coat.

Assembly! Take one of the toasted buns and spread Sir Kensingtons Avocado oil mayo on the bottom bun. Then add pickles, the chicken thigh, and shredduce-y slaw. Take the top bun and add 1/4 of the mashed avocado. Add the top bun and boom! You have the best chicken sandwich you will ever have.
ENJOY!

slaw mix or combination of carrots and cabbage

directions.Direction: Start by food processing the carrots and cabbage if you are not using a Cole slaw mix.

Add some oil to a very large pan and heat to medium-high. Add the pork in clumps, season with salt and pepper, and leave undisturbed to cook for 3-5 minutes, until the bottoms are nice and crispy. Stir and break up the pork and continue to cook until fully cooked through and no pink remains.
Add in the garlic and ginger and immediately mix well. Let that cook for about 30 seconds before adding in the other ingredients.
Add in the veggie mix (Cole slaw or carrots and cabbage) and cook until wilted, about 5 minutes stirring often.
Add the green onions, 1 tbsp soy sauce, and sesame oil. Mix well and taste for seasoning. You may need to add extra soy sauce. Let cool completely.

Get your spring roll station ready with the cooled filling, egg roll wrappers, and some water. Working one at a time add 2 tbsp to the lower portion of the wrapper, making sure there is space around the edges. Dip your finger in water and gently brush the perimeter of the wrapper. First fold in the sides, then roll the spring roll onto itself. Continue with the remaining rolls - you should have exactly 20.
Fry in tallow or other oil over medium heat until crispy and golden on all sides. Timing will all depend on how deep and hot your oil is. Let drain and cool on a wire rack.
To make the plum sauce:
Combine all the ingredients in a sauce pan and bring to a boil. Lower the heat to medium and simmer for about 20-25 minutes.
Use a hand blender (or normal blender but make sure it's fully cooled then) until it is totally smooth.

directions.Direction: Prep all of your veggies: The celery should be cut in thirds length wise, then chopped up to make 1/4 in cubes. The shallot should be a rough yet fine chop. For the radishes you'll cut off the top and bottom (where the stem and roots are) then cut into thin rounds. The cucumbers will get the same treatment as the radish, so cut off the top and bottom then thinly slice. The capers should be finely chopped. The pickle chips should be finely chopped. And the avocado will be thinly sliced and then spread apart to create that beautiful presentation cado.

Mixie mix your tuna, celery, shallot, capers, pickles, lemon juice, mayo, mustard, paprika, and salt and pep. Taste for seasoning, but remember that it's also going on top of 2 slices of bread, some cheese, and other veggies. So the brightness will be toned down.

Toast your slices of bread in a skillet over medium heat with some butter. I like to toast both sides, so I toast, flip, then top with cheese, lower temp to low, cover with a lid, and allow that to melt.

Remove from the heat and top the cheese-less piece with 1/2 of the tuna mixture, then a layer of cucumber slices, a layer of radish, the avocado slices, and some lettuce. Last but not least, top with your cheesy piece of bread.
So pro tip here if you want a cheese pull. It's annoying, but you'll have to cut the sandwich, remove the cheesy bread, and pop that under the broiler for the cheese to re-melt together.
Anyways. ENJOY!!!

Description:
I grew up eating tuna fish sandwiches. My siblings and I would essentially dump every dried spice we had into the mixture and just devourrr. Like the first time I went from having plain tuna salad to tuna salad with paprika, garlic powder, onion powder, cayenne, cumin, dill, salt, pepper, etc etc etc, it was life changing. 

Albeit that's not how I like it now, but still. Life changing. 

This rendition is veggie forward and really packs on a lot of celery. Not a fan of celery? Well don't worry it's smothered and covered in so much flavorful mayo-ey sauce that all you'll detect is the crunch. 

One of my biggest issues with a mayo heavy tuna salad is that it just feels unbalanced. Like all this richness and no acidity or bitterness. So I tackle both! We have bright dijon, briney pickles, and bitter radishes. 

I live laugh love this sandwich.
Notes: Tuna can be stored in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 3 days.
