ingredients.Name: Hot dog buns (Homemade is obviously the way to go here...)
Hot dogs (I used Boar's Head Uncured Beef Frankfurters which are longer)
finely chopped green olives (I like castelvetrano)
Thinly sliced white or yellow onion

directions.Direction: I made the buns using Joshua Weissman's recipe, but honestly I would tweak the size measurements. I'm linking it below, but where he says to roll the log to 4 1/2 in I would do 6 to 7 inches for these special spiral dogs. Basically just look at the size dog you have, if it's a normal sized dog I'd do 6 inches, if it's a longer dog like the one I used I'd do 7. When you spiral the dog they grow in length! https://www.joshuaweissman.com/post/homemade-hot-dog-buns

Prepare the relish by combining the cornichons, olives, capers, and sweet relish. Add 1 tbsp olive oil, mix, and see if it binds it all. Use your judgement if you want to add up to 1 tbsp more. *If you LOVE relish I'd recommend doubling the quantity of everything!*

Let's spiral those dogs! Use a kebab stick / skewer and go through the center of the hot dog. Then, using a small paring knife, slice through the dog at an angle until you hit the kebab and spin the dog around until you go through the entire length of the hot dog. Basically you can keep the knife in one spot, at an angle, and just roll the dog. It'll essentially move down the length of the dog on its own. Remove the stick and repeat with all of your hot dogs.

Heat your grill or stovetop - you want it ripping hot! I wouldn't recommend using a grill without a cast iron baking sheet or other pan since the spiral makes the dogs a little more delicate. Add some oil to the pan and cook until the edges around the cuts are browning/charing and the dog is fully cooked. Make sure you're rotating and rolling around the dogs so all the sides get evenly cooked. As it cooks the spiral will become more defined.
Assemble: Add a spiral dog to your hotdog bun (slice the bun if you made them yourself), followed with mustard AND ketchup, then thinly sliced onion, and the relish.
ENJOY!

ingredients.Name: maple syrup, coconut sugar, or regular sugar
kefir (can sub buttermilk OR 1/2 milk 1/2 yogurt) 160g
olive oil, plus more for the pan

directions.Direction: Preheat an 8in pan on the lower end of medium-low, not all the way low... but like a quarter between low and medium.
Combine dry ingredients in a bowl and give them a mixie mix.
Combine wet ingredients in a separate bowl and give them a mixie mix.
Add dry to wet and you guessed it! Mixie mix
Add in blueberries... mixie mix just to combine.
Add about 2 tablespoons olive oil to the preheated pan and add in your batter.

Cover with the lid and let it slowly fry for about 20 minutes. You can check on the bottom every once in a while to ensure it's not burning, but if you keep it at the low-medium/low temp and rotate the pan every once in awhile you should be good! You know it's ready when there is no wetness on top of the pancake and it looks pretty evenly puffed even in the center. (it can be wet/damp to the touch, but we don't want ooey gooey batter left ya know?)

Ok flipping... I like to use a rubber spatula to get up under it, sort of slide it out of the pan, tilt the pan, and then flip it. It'll take some practice so even if you fold it in half just know it'll still taste delicious and next time you'll nail it.
Once flipped let it cook for another 5 minutes on that low-medium/low temp.
Top with two lil slices of butter, some flaky salt, and tonz of maple syrup.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: THE Blueberry Sourdough Pancake
Description:
*makes one pancake but that serves 2 people*

After a great deal of recipe testing, I finally developed THE Blueberry Sourdough Pancake. 

Seriously though it’s slow fried in olive oil which makes it crispy, the perfect match between doughy and pancakey, the perrrrfect level of sweetness with a hint of salty from the flaky salt on top, and I mean anything smothered and covered in butter and maple syrup is a win in my book. 

I opted for Kefir instead of buttermilk (traditionally found in pancakes) because 1. I usually have Kefir in my fridge and 2. probiotics baby!

Really really really happy with this one and I hope you will be too!

*If you typically discard 200g of starter you can absolutely double this recipe. That's also a great edit for a bigger crowd, just remember you'll need two pans.

directions.Direction: Start by boiling the water. Add matcha powder to a 32oz glass jar, pour in the boiling water, and use a milk frother or matcha whisk to mixie mix it up.
Add in the coconut water to cool it all down
In another vessel, add spirulina, honey, vanilla, and milk. Use the frother to mixie mix dat up.

Add in your pinch of salt and pepper if using. Totally optional but it does add an extra something something to this. Annnnnd salt and pepper both have added health benefits so is it really even optional? I don't think so.
Fill up the matcha jar up with as much or as little ice as ya want, but boy do I love these sphere ice cubes. Then top it off with your blue milky mix and enjoy the show.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Blue Iced Matcha Latte
Description:
This beautttttiful drink is delicious, nutritious, n let's just be honest... it's like really fun to drink something so pretty. 

Blue Spirulina and Matcha are both health food powerhouses and then you get the added bonus of hydration from the coconut water !!

This is like a matcha latte you've never had!

ingredients.Name: Demerara or Turbinado sugar for topping

directions.Direction: Heat oven to 375F.
Line 12 muffin tins with cupcake liners OR, my personal favorite, sheets of parchment. If you’re going parchment they’ll be about 6x6in squares. Grease the muffin tins so the parchment sticks.

First things first you wanna toast your nutz. Give them a lil chop, add to a pan, and cook over medium heat for about 3-5 minutes, stirring occasionally. You just wanna toast, not burn! Then remove from pan and allow to cool.
While that’s happening, give your choco chipz a chop. It doesn’t have to be perfect, I just like having some chocolate dust in the mix.
Okie dokie onto the business. Add butter, white sugar, brown sugar, vanilla, and eggs to a large bowl. Use a whisk to mixie mix that all up until the mixture is light and fluffy.
Mash up the bananas in a bowl or on a cutting board and add to the sugar mixture. Mixie mix!
Sprinkle on the baking power, baking soda, and salt. Mixie mix to fully incorporate. Then sprinkle on the all purpose flour and almond flour. And, you guessed it, mixie mix.

Now move onto a rubber spatula and mix in 1/2 cup nuts and 1/2 cup choco chips. Don’t over mix here, just stir and fold until the additions are fully incorporated. Use a 1/4 cup measuring cup to fill the muffin tins. You’ll have about 1/2 cup leftover so just evenly distribute that among the muffins until all of the batter is used and everything looks even.
Top with the remaining 1/4 cup nuts and 1/4 cup chocolate chips, and add some Demerara or turbinado sugar on top for extra sparkle and yum.
Bake for 18-22 minutes, or until the muffins are puffed up and a toothpick comes out clean when inserted into the center.
Let them cool in the pan for 10 minutes then remove and cool on a wire rack.
I loveeeee these with some extra butter on top cause that’s just delish, but you do you.
ENJOY!!!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Banana Nut Muffinz
Description:
These may be the best muffins I have ever made. FULL STOP. 
I’m not kidding they’re truly so delicious that I have to actively keep myself from eating like 4 at at time. As I eat my second one of the day….
NOT TO MENTION they’re so stupid easy to make. Literally one bowl… you don’t even need to mix the dry ingredients separately. 

Here is how you do it 😎

ingredients.Name: divided, 1 for coating the pan and 1 for topping the baby

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 425F and pop in a 10in cast iron pan so it can heat up as well.
Add everything (minus da banana) to a blender and blend, scraping down the sides once or twice, until it’s blended. EASY. And if you don’t use a blender literally just whisk it by hand.
Once preheated, add 1 tbsp butter to your hot AF cast iron and coat the pan evenly. Add your banana slices and top it with with your baby mix.
Cook at 425F for 12-15 minutes or until she is puffed, golden, and very cute.
Whisk whipping cream until soft peaks form. Add sugar, salt, and whisk again until medium peaks happen. Gently mixie mix in your yog and you are good to go baby.
Add toppings and enjoy!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: very Berry DUTCH BABY
Description:
The worlds easiest (and like somehow most impressive) brunch party meal.

While you don’t neeeeeed a blender it does make it like a million times easier, so you do you boo.
Top your baby with whatever you want, but if it’s not berries, greek yog whipped cream, n’ honey then what are you doing dude.
Oh and also this isn’t topped with maple syrup, no. That’s lame. THIS IS TOPPED WITH HONEY. Cause that’s how we treat baby.

directions.Direction: For The Pancake
Whisk to combine flour, baking powder, and salt. Set aside.

Whisk the eggs, then add in the banana, give it a smoosh, then blueberries, smoooosh, then chia seeds, melted ghee, and syrup. Mixie mix then add to the dry ingredients. Stir only until combined and set aside. This rest time is vital as the flour will hydrate and baking powder will activate and puff up the batter. About 5 minutes while your griddle heats up.

Set your griddle or pan to medium low and slather that baby in ghee (or butter if you don’t have ghee). Once hot, dollop 1/4-1/3 ish cup portions and smoosh those down to be about 4 inches in diameter. They’ll spread to about 5-6in as they cook. Give them about 2 minutes on each side, or until slightly crispy and golden.
For The Topping
While cooking, mix your yogurt and maple syrup topping. I’m not encouraging anyone to eat all of these at once, so get your serving and top it as you please.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Healthyish Whole Wheat Blueberry Pancakes
Description: These also have BANANAS, but that would’ve been a lil too wordy for a caption ya know? Not joking when I say these may be the best pancakes I’ve ever had. Don’t sleep on the yogurt topping, it’s unreal yumm and obvs has extra protein baby.

ingredients.Name: almond extract, rum would be great subbed here
powdered sugar, to your taste preference

directions.Direction: Combine flour, baking powder, and salt in a large bowl. Set aside
Combine butter, eggs, brown sugar, vanilla extract, almond extract, and poppyseeds in a large bowl. Whisk until everything is smooth and combined. Add in the milk and mixie mix again.
Combine dry and wet ingredients using your whisk. Mix just until combined and then stopppp!
Plop in all of your banana bits and mix until everything is fully coated.

Add butter or oil to a large pan and set it over medium heat. Once up to temp start adding in banana pancake pieces! I like to use a spoon here so I can grab not only the banana, but some pancake batter along with it. Cook for about 3 minutes on each side, or until nice and golden! Repeat until all banana bits are cooked.

While that’s cooking you can make your yogurt whipped cream sauce. I like to whisk the cream until firm peaks form, then add in yogurt and sugar. The yogurt will thin it out to a sauce-like consistency, but if you want it to retain the whipped cream peaks either eliminate the yogurt addition or just add less.
Once everything is cooked, top with all dat yogurt whipped cream sauce, maple syrup, and some extra powdered sugar.
They’re so so so good and really fun. ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Mini Poppyseed BANANA Pancakez
Description:
They’re so stinking cute and outrageously easy to eat. 
I used suuuuper ripe bananas because well, I didn’t want them to go bad. But you can use any ripeness that makes you happy!
Just keep in mind that the riper they are, the sweeter these lil mini banana pancakes will be. 

Poppyseeds are totally optional in this, but I think they add a nice texture and flavor. 

It’s all topped with a yogurty whipped cream sauce, maple syrup, and some powdered sugar. 

This is definitely meant to be shared, so go find some friends, family, loved ones, neighbors, strangers, or weirdos to enjoy this with. ❤️

ingredients.Name: For The Cheddar Bacon Chive Frittata
sugar free bacon, cooked and crushed
chives, thinly sliced into teeny tiny chivey tubez

directions.Direction: For The Cheddar Bacon Chive Frittata
Preheat oven to 350F.
Cook your bacon in a 9-10in cast iron, cook bacon, then pour out grease but leaving behind a greased slick pan.
Mix eggs and mix milk in until nice and smooth. Add salt n pep to season. Add in cheese, bacon, and chives. Mixie mix.
Add that mix to your prepped cast iron pan and bake for 35-45 minutes or until fullllly cooked, puffed, crisping, and starting to brown.
For The Chia Seed Jam

Add everything (except honey) to a saucepan and cook over medium-low with the lid on until everything is melted, stirring frequently. Once melted allow that to simmer on low for 3-5 minutes or until slightly thicken.
Add in honey and mash that baby up. Pour into vessels and if you need to eat it quickly you can pop it in the freezer, otherwise place it in the fridge to firm up.
For The Almond Flour Biscuits
I used the recipe by Melissa’s Southern Style Kitchen but subbed 1/2 plain Bulgarian yogurt and 1/2 whole milk in place of buttermilk.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: GIRLS BRUNCH but make it Gluten Free

directions.Direction: Toast, toasted!
Avocado, sliced!
Chives, mini tubez!
Flakey salt, sprinklin!
For The Candied Bacon

Preheat the oven to 425F, bake the bacon on a wire rack, flip after 10 minutes, bake another 2 minutes, then remove. Slather on some maple syrup mixed with smoked paprika, and then place back in the oven for another 5ish or until nice and crispy. The cook times will vary depending on your bacon’s thickness, so just keep an eye on it.
For The Soft Scramble

Start with a cold non-stick pan and add the butter and eggs. Turn the heat to medium-low and start scramblin with ideally chopsticks. Cook until some larger curds are forming, then create lil eggy mounds, turn it to low, cover with a lid, and cook for 3-5 minutes.
Assemble, and enjoy.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Eggy Avocado Toast w/ CANDIED Bacon
Description: A lil soft scrambled eggz and maple candied bacon. I’m even drooling.

ingredients.Name: cooked sushi rice (were talkin leftovers here folks)

directions.Direction: You know I love a choose your own adventure kind of meal.

Start by adding about 1-2tbsp oil to a 9in cast iron pan and set that over medium-high heat. Add your rice and use a spatula to smooooosh it down and form nice and clean edges. Season with salt n pep.
I alsoooo used some ghee around the edges and dolloped some on top of the rice for added flavor baby.
Cook for about 5-7 minutes, then add your eggies to the party. Use the spatula to clean up the egg edges too.
You know the drill, salt n pep. Top with as much parm as your heart desires.
Listen, if you’re really cool you can flip this whole thing. But alas, I’m not that cool. So I just break it up into sections and flip dat.
You still get the super duper crispy rice chunks so don’t worry.
Cook for about 2 more minutes to fully cook your eggs then remove from heat.

Add some rice egg mix to a bowl, top with super duper thinly sliced cucumber (I like to use a Y peeler and peel on a bias), then add cottage cheese, thennnnn add chili crisp. If you’re feeling wild you can add the other toppings I suggested, but deffo add flaky salt.
Bone apple teet.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: CRISPY Rice n Eggz
Description:
This is so stupid easy.

Things that you could *and should* do to make this better, add bacon, an extra jammy egg, and avocado. Why didn’t I do these things you might ask? Because I didn’t have bacon or cado and I needed all of my eggs for other projects.
moving onnnnnn.

ingredients.Name: unbleached bread flour, wait to add the last 1/2 cup after you check the dough

directions.Direction: Combine everything (minus sugar) in a stand mixer and knead for 10 minutes.
Rest for 45-60 minutes or until doubled.
Punch down and divide into 8 pieces (about 160 grams each)
*I personally rolled into balls, rested for 20 minutes, then rolled into lil snake. I twisted it around my hand, and rubbed it against the counter to seal.*
Preheat oven to 400F
Fill a large pot with water and the 2 tbsp sugar, bring to a boil.
Once boiling, cook 4 at a time for 30 seconds on each side.
While wet you can dunk in your toppings! I did a “bagel mix” that I made at home.
Bake at 400F on a baking sheet for 30 minutes, rotating half way through to ensure even browning.
Let cool a bit before cutting in
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Sourdough Discard Bagels
Description:
I mean who doesn’t love a homemade bagel?! Seriously. 
These have the added health benefit of utilizing sourdough discard, but without all the wait time. 

For this first round of sourdough bagels I really wanted to find a recipe that could be made same day (so no overnight ferment) and that didn’t have barley malt or diastatic malt. Because honestly who has that laying around in their pantry? Not me. 
(However I may try to sub barley malt for blackstrap molasses next time because I already have an love that)

I sourced this recipe from Thyme from The Table and it reads as follows:
Notes:
*If you're making a bacon egg and cheese, the cheese that's gonna give you MAX cheese pull is mozzarella!!! Monterey Jack is also good, cheddar is decent. 
*You can access the original recipe here! https://thymeforthetable.com/bagels-with-sourdough-discard/#recipe

ingredients.Name: sprigs of scallion (green onion), finely chopped into tiny lil scallion tubez
large slices of thick ham or like 4 pieces of thin deli ham, chopped into 1/2 in ish pieces

directions.Direction: Heat bone broth in a small saucepan or in the microwave until hot and drinkable. (Bone broth gives you protein, collagen, and tons of salt and minerals to start your day off right)
Heat ghee or butter in a medium skillet over medium heat.
Add in ham and cook for 2-3 minutes to get it sizzling and browning.
Lower the heat to medium-low. Add in the scallions and cook for 1 minute, just until the green color brightens and becomes more vibrant.

Pour in the eggs, push them around a bit to scramble them up, then let them rest spread out in an even-ish layer. Season will a little salt n' pep... but ham and chedz are SALTY so a tiny bit goes a long way.
Add some cheddar cheese, then fold it up to be sort of omlette-ish. Not totally necessary, but a little more ~special~.
Top with extra cheddar cheese!
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Ham and Scallion Omletteish n’ Bone Broth
Description:
Just a proper, protein filled brekkie to get you through the day!

I love using ham in breakfast scrambled because it's so darn easy. If you have deli meat on hand this is a great way to use it as well!

Plussss you know I love to grow my own scallions so I might as well use them. And if you don't grow them, they're incredibly cheap!

ingredients.Name: Toppings: whole milk green yogurt, nuts of choice, fruit of choice

directions.Direction: Add quinoa, bone broth, and whole milk to a medium pot. Mixie mix to combine.
Add in syrup, vanilla, and cinnamon. Mixie Mix.
Bring to a gentle simmer and let it simmer away for 15 minutes.
Once the liquid has been almost totally absorbed add in butter and collagen. Mixie mix.
Spoon into your fav lil bowl and top with whatever toppings you like!
Enjoy!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Quinoa wit Nuts, Fruit, and Greek YOGGGGG
Description:
TIME:  20 ⏰
SERVINGS: 2 adults🧍🧍
DIETARY SPECS: High protein, High Fiber, Gluten-Free 💪🥬

I NEED my breakfast to be jam slam packed with nutrients and proteins to get me through the day. 

We make swap out the water for BONE BROTH and WHOLE MILK to really pack on the protein (not to mention quinoa packs a whopping 8g per cup!!)

You may be thinking… does it taste like bone broth? And the answer is NO. 
With the addition of cinnamon, vanilla, and maple syrup the flavor profile reads SWEET! Which is what we want. 

I add in butter for extra fat and creaminess and collagen powder for extra, well… collagen and health benefits!

You can choose any nuts and fruit you like, but I went with sliced almonds, pumpkin seeds, persimmon, and banana. 

And because I reallllly wanted to pack on the protein here, I topped it all off with some plain whole milk greek yogurt. 

Truly delicious!

ingredients.Name: hefty handfuls of baby spinach leaves
ish cup of feta, crumbled up
Some hummusssss! I used @eatlittlesesame jammy tomato

directions.Direction: Heat ghee or butter in a skillet over medium heat.
Once melted add in spinach and sauté for a minute or two, just until wilted.
Add in feta.  **And we’re not going for fried crispy feta… just warmed slightly melted feta so it incorporates into all the eggs but still leaves some chunks. It’s as good as it sounds.**
Pour in eggs and just scramble those up.
Season with salt and pep.
While all that is happening you can either 1. Leave the pita room temp 2. Heat it in a pan or the oven or 3. Heat it over an open flame on a gas range. You obvs know which I would choose. 😎
Cut the pita in half, open up the lil pita pockets, slather the insides with dat hummus, stuff it with the egg mixture and boom.
You’re done.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Spinach n’ Feta Pita Scramble
Description:
TIME:  10 ⏰
SERVINGS: 1 very hungry adult🧍
DIETARY SPECS: High protein 💪

IT’S PORTABLE. IT’S HIGH PROTEIN. IT’S DELISH. 

It’s quite possibly my new favorite breakfast. 

The feta gets melty while still retaining chunkzzzzz, the hummus adds brightness, the spinach gives nutrients, eggs bringing dat protein, and pita just making this the most portable and delicious soft lil twist on a breakfast sammie. 😎 (I love a good run-on sentence)

For real though, this is the perfecttttt brekkie to take with you when you’re on the go. 
But it’s also all I’m craving soooo eat it whenever. 

Daniel ate his with some hot sauce 🔥

ingredients.Name: medium sweet potato, diced into 1/2 in cubez

directions.Direction: Heat a large skillet over medium heat and melt 2 tbsp butter.
Add in onion and pepper and cook until softened and starting to brown. About 2-4 minutes

Add in sweet potatoes, make sure everything is coated in butter. Sprinkle with your seasonings, mixie mix, and cover with a lid at a tilt so some steam escapes. Cook on medium-low for 8-12 minutes or until the sweet potatoes are soft, stirring occasionally so nothing burns.
Remove from the pan, increase temp to medium, add oil, and fry your egg(s). I like to fry them on medium heat. Make sure you're rotating the pan around so all of the edges get hit with oil!
Assemble with your desired toppings but I like to use: cheddar cheese, greek yog, fried egg, cilantro, and lime!
ENJOYYYY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Sweet Potato Breakfast Hash
Description:
TIME:  25 ⏰
SERVINGS: 2 adults🧍
DIETARY SPECS: High protein, High Fiber, Grain Free 💪
DAY: 4 / 100 🗓️

This Sweet Potato Breakfast Hash will carry you through the day!! 🍠

It’s packed with nutrients and protein and it’s absotootly deeeeelicious. 😎

It takes about 10 minutes to cook down those sweet potatoes, so this isn’t a breakfast you make on a morning when you hit dat snooze button… but if you find yourself with a litttttle extra time in the morning, MAKE THIS! 

You could also prep the peppers, onions, and potatoes ahead of time and just warm them up in the morning. 
We love a good meal prep hack. 🧅🫑

ingredients.Name: mixed frozen berries (mine was blueberry, blackberry, cherry)

directions.Direction: Combine egg, milk, cinnamon, and vanilla in a large bowl. Mixie mix until totally combined!
Dunk in the slice of bread and flip that until it absorbs a majority of the mixture.
While the bread is soaking, heat 1 tbsp butter in a skillet over medium heat.
Once the bread is soaked and butter is melted, add the bread to the pan.

In an effort to maximize my protein intake and not waste precious food, I spoon the eggy milky mix over the top of the bread. All the little holes and nooks and crannies will become vessels to hold onto that extra mixture.
Cook for about 2-4 minutes on the first side, flip, and cook another 2-4ish. You want both sides to be crowned and custard set!
Once the French toast is out of the pan just add in the berries to heat up. The heat will help bring out the natural sweetness of the berries.
To assemble add ricotta to the toast, then hot/warm berries, then some flaky salt and a touch of maple syrup.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Very Berry Ricotta French Toast
Description:
TIME:  15 ⏰
SERVINGS: 1 adult🧍
DIETARY SPECS: Refined Sugar Free, Antioxidant Rich, Protein 💪
DAY: 5 / 100 🗓️

It’s every bit as good as you’d expect. 😎

ACTUALLY, if I’m being truthful, this was WAY better than I expected. 👏🏻

I don’t think breakfast should be very sweet, I mean hello glucose spikes, so I made sure this was minimally sweet while still having the sweet profile you’re expecting. 

Between the creamy ricotta, tart berries, and SOURDOUGH French toast, the flavor combos are phenom. ✨
It’s like when Remy in Ratatouille eats the grape and cheese, it’s magic. 🐀

Not to mention the custard mix and ricotta will give you enough protein to sustain you through the morning!

ingredients.Name: of water (yeah I didn’t do bone broth today…)
peanut butter (or any nut butter you like)
scoop protein powder (I like @wellious.co cuz it’s super clean ingredients)
Toppings: plain greek yog, crushed up nuts

directions.Direction: Cook oats in salted water according to package details. Aka, bring water and salt to a boil, then add in oats, then lower the temp, cover, and cook until the water is absorbed and oats are soft. Feel free to scale this whole thing up if you want leftovers!
Once cooked add in butter, peanut butter, protein powder, and collagen. Mixie mix to combine/melt.
It’s gonna be pretttttty darn thick at this point so add in 2-4 tbsp milk until it’s your desire consistency. You may even want more. You do you!
Top with yogurt and crushed nuts.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Chocolate Peanut Butter Protein Oatz
Description:
TIME:  15 ⏰
SERVINGS: 1 adult🧍
DIETARY SPECS: High Protein, Gluten Free 💪
DAY: 6 / 100 🗓️

Some days you just want a big ol’ bowl of oatz ya know?

This is always so perfect after a heavy workout where I don’t really want to put in a lot of work and I want to replenish my body and get protein and eat something warm. 😘

So yeah oats are cool and actually have a really high amount of calcium…
But there are a couple must haves for me if I’m gonna eat them: 
1. It’s gotta still be packed with fat and protein so we’re doing a double whammy with peanut butter and some chocolate protein. 🥜 Plus butter cuz YUM 🧈🍫 Plussss plain greek yog cuz YES
2. The oats gotta be sprouted, organic, and glyphosate free. This isn’t sponsored at all, I just really like @onedegreeorganics and their quality. 👏🏻

So go crush that workout and then eat this. 💪

ingredients.Name: honey, plus more for drizzle (maple syrup works too!)
AP or whole wheat einkorn (you can sub regular flour, but you'll lose out on some protein and nutrients)

directions.Direction: Whisk together wet ingredients.
Add flour and salt and whisk once again to combine.

Heat 1 tbsp (per batch) of butter in a large skillet over medium heat. Once melted add in pancake batter by the 1/4 cup. I like my pancakes to get a little dark and crispy, so I just pay attention to what the edges of the pancake looks like. This usually takes 3ish minutes on my stove. You can always use a spatula to gently lift the pancake to test for your desired doneness. Flip and cook for another 1-2 minutes.
I like to add berries in between each layer of pancake AND on top. I top the whole stack with more honey, flaky salt, and that's it!
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Cottage Cheese Pancakes
Description:
There are a lot of cottage cheese pancake recipes out there, but this one is unique for so many reasons. 

1. It is refined sugar free and is instead made and topped with raw honey for added nutrients. 
2. They have tons of protein to sustain you through your morning. 
3. Which is my favorite, you can eyeball measure these and they still work. 

plus they're made with einkorn which has 29% more protein than conventional flour, is more easily digestible, and is packed with nutrients. 

They're my perfect cottage cheese pancake.

ingredients.Name: ish cup extra virgin olive oil

directions.Direction: Combine water, 2 tsp honey, and mixie mix to combine. Sprinkle the yeast on top and let sit for a couple minutes to ensure the yeast is active and blooming. If the yeast mixture never foams up, it may be dead so get some fresh yeast and start over! Orrrrr if you know your yeast is good just move on.
In a large bowl add 6 cups (720g. bread flour) and 2 tsp salt, whisk to combine.

Pour in the yeast and water mixture. And use your hands or a flexible bowl scraper to mix everything together until no dry spots remain. It’ll still seem a bit shaggy, clumpy, not smooth, you get the idea.
Cover with a damp towel and let rise until doubled in size, about 60ish minutes.

After your dough has doubled in size, do a series of stretches and folds. Wet one hand with filtered water and slip it under the dough, lift up to stretch, and fold it on top of itself. Rotate 90 degrees and repeat 3 times for a total of 4 stretches and folds.
Let it rise again for another 45-60 minutes, or until doubled.

Using either baking dish of your choice (either a 18in.x12in.x1in. or 9in.x12in.x 3in), coat the entire thing in olive oil and use your fingers to spread it around. Gently dump out your risen dough. Add some oil to your hands and encourage the dough to flatten and stretch out. The gluten will be a bit tight at this point, so just try to flatten it as much as possible. It will continue to spread as it puffs up.
Cover and allow to rise undisturbed until it has puffed up, about 45ish minutes.
Preheat your oven to 425F.
Add some more oil to your hands and poke the dough all over.

Add the toppings of your choice or nothing at all (garlic, onions, tomatoes, herbs, cheese, if you can think of it, it will probably work!), drizzle with more olive oil, sprinkle with flakey salt, and you are ready to go.

Bake for 20 minutes, rotate so it gets evenly browned, and then cook for another 20-25 minutes depending on your desired crispy golden goodness level. You’re looking for very golden, very brown, very crispy.
Remove from the oven and allow to cool in the pan for 10 minutes. Then remove it from the pan and allow to fully cool before cutting. If you can…
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: THICK Focaccia
Description:
This is a THICK and pretty dense focaccia. I personally like it this way so I can easily use it with sandwiches. 
The best part about this recipe is that you can go from start to finish in 3ish hours. Yes, focaccia in 3 hours. 
So with that being said, is it tradish? No. Is it delish? Yes.

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 325F and prep a loaf. I use an 8.5 x 4.5 cast iron loaf pan. To do so, coat the loaf pan with oil or butter and cut a piece of parchment paper to fit along the bottom and up the sides of the pan. So only the sides of the short portions will be showing. This gives you little parchment handles to grab the loaf out of the pan once it’s cooked and cooled. You get me? If not watch the video!

*Tip: get an oven thermometer for this recipe so you can make sure your oven is actually the temp it says. If your oven is running hot the loaf will likely rise too quickly and balloon over the sides. If your oven is running low then you may be left with a dense and gummy crumb.

Mixie mix flour, baking powder, salt, and cinnamon in a medium sized bowl. The addition of cinnamon really helps you see when everything is fully mixed. It’s so common to under-mix dry ingredients, so this will help you see truly how much you should be mixing! Set aside.

Time to brown the butter. Add butter to a small pot set over medium heat. Whisk the butter occasionally to make sure no milk solids are sticking to the bottom. Depending on how high your heat actually is the time will vary. In all it should take approximately 5 minutes, but visual cues are what you should be paying attention to. The butter will start bubbling up vigorously as the water in the butter boils off. The bubbles will being to get smaller and smaller and bubbling noises will calm down. You want to pay close attention because once the bubbles turn to sort of a foamy film on top and the milk solids (teeny tiny specks of brown) are a light toasty color you NEED to remove it from the heat. The residual heat will continue to toast the milk solids so you want to err on the lower side of toasted when you remove it from the heat. Another cue is a super toasty, buttery smell. The toasted solids sort of look like brown vanilla bean seeds!
To speed up the cooling I add the bowl to another bowl with ice cubes in it. That’ll just gently accelerate the cooling so you’re not waiting forever to continue with the recipe.

In a large bowl combine pumpkin, eggs, yogurt, vanilla, brown sugar, and cooled brown butter. *If you can’t find bourbon vanilla just do 1 1/2 tsp vanilla and 1/2 tsp bourbon.* Mixie mix until fully smooth and combined.

Add in 1/2 of the flour mixture and gently mix to combine. Add in the remaining 1/2 of the flour and once again gently mix. You want to ONLY mix until no dry spots remain. Make sure you’re scraping the bottom and sides of the bowl to ensure there are no lingering bits of flour left.
Pour into your prepped loaf pan and smooth out the top.

Bake on the middle rack for approximately 75-90 minutes. You want to go until a toothpick or cake tester comes out clean when poked into the thickest part of the loaf, but that could still mean the bottom is slightly under done. Another visual cue is to let the top of the loaf BEGIN to slightly brown. I’m not saying brown or crisp, but like hints of it starting to do so. You can also listen to the cake! You want gentle noises of fizz… as you bake more that’ll make more sense. Worst case the bottom has a teeny tiny line of underdone batter (like mine did in the video) and I assure you it is still so delicious.
Allow the cake to cool in the loaf pan for 20 minutes.
Then remove using the parchment handles and place it on a wire cooling rack and allow it to cool like this for another 20 minutes.
Thennnn remove the parchment so the bottom of the loaf can properly cool and air out as well.
Let the loaf FULLY cool (to the touch, approximately 1-2 hours) before topping it with your cream cheese frosting.

While the cake is cooling make the cream cheese frosting. To do so whisk the cream cheese until smooth, then add powdered/confectioners sugar, vanilla, and a pinch of salt. Vigorously whisk to combine and try to incorporate some air into it.
Spread cream cheese frosting on the top of the loaf and add pumpkin seeds for garnish.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Brown Butter Bourbon Pumpkin Loaf
Description:
This isn’t any ol’ pumpkin loaf, it’s a BROWN BUTTER pumpkin loaf with a deliiiiicious cream cheese frosting. And nothing smells more like Fall to me than a brown butter. 🍂

Like truly this is a perfect recipe for your next Fall weekend indoors. 

It requires no special equipment and is totally beginner friendly. Trust me, you can do it. 

It is DELICIOUS and honestly stays delicious for days after making it. Just make sure you refrigerate it to keep the cream cheese from spoiling. That is, if you don’t eat the whole thing immediately. 🤤

ingredients.Name: dark brown sugar (you can totally sub light if that’s all you have)

directions.Direction: Let’s prep the choco chipz first! Separate the chips into two even piles. One pile is going to get chopped! And you want to chop until every single piece has been chopped at least once. This will cause a ton of chocolate dust and that’s eggzactly what I’m going for here! Then the chocolate permeates the entire cookie. Like a speckled chocolate chip cookie wonderland! The other half will remain whole, but separate another 2ish tbsp from that and set it aside.
Combine flour, salt, and baking soda in a medium sized bowl. Really whisk it more than you think it needs to be whisked… dry ingredients can be tricky like dat.

Add butter and both sugars to a stand mixer fitted with a paddle attachment. You can totally do this with a hand mixer or by hand, but the stand mixer is the easiest and most consistent for me. You’ll definitely get a workout doing this by hand, by more power to ya! ANYWAYS! Mixie mix on medium-high until the batter is light and fluffy, stopping once or twice to scrape down the bowl, but in total should be about 3 minutes.
Then add in eggz and vanilla, and beat on medium again for about 2 minutes. Scrape down the bowl, then mix for another 30 seconds. You just want it to incorporate, then get evennnn fluffier.
Add in your dry ingredients and mix just until combined. Scrape the bowl, then pulse/mix 1-3 more times.
Add in the chopped chips n’ dust and whole chocolate chips (still reserving that other 2 tbsp). Mix on medium-low for 10 seconds just to combine!
Use your spatula to scrape down the sides and bottom of the bowl and make sure that the chips are evenly distributed.
Next use two spoons, or a cookie scoop, to scoop out 16 even ballz/clumpz. It’ll be about 2ish heaping tbsp. Top with the remaining chocolate chips, some flaky salt, and thennnn FREEZE!

Let the dough chill in the freezer for at least one hour OR you can let it hang in the fridge for up to 48hours. You can also just commit to the freezer and let them hang out for about 2 months for cookies on demand! Pretty unfussy with this part.

Once you’re ready to cook, preheat the oven to 425F and make sure you bake the cookies on a room temp, parchment lined baking sheet. If you use the frozen/cold baking sheet they won’t cook properly. Keep the cookies about 2in apart!

Bake at 425F for 5 minutes, then lower the temp to 350F and bake another 10 minutes. At this point they’re still going to be pretty smooshy… but that’s ok. Use a 3.5-4in cookie cutter and scoop the cookie into the center. Make a quick circle motion to collect the cookie together and encourage it to be a round shape. Repeat with all cookies.
Bake for another 5 minutes, then repeat cookie cutter technique.

Thennnn top with flaky salt and I promise this is the final time back in the oven and it’s actually optional…. but if you want to fully set the cookies and get a little more browning and crispiness to them, pop it under the broiler for 2 minutes. But please please please keep an eye on them!!! You’ve worked so hard, now is not the time to burn them ya know.
Cook them on a wire rack and thennn
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: THE Chocolate Chip Cookiezzz
Description:
THE Chocolate Chip Cookiezzz

These are THEEEE Chocolate Chip Cookies. 😎
They’re a lil crunchy, a lil doughy, and a lot delishhhh.

AND they’re freaking stunning. Like the little chocolatey rivers and puddles n’ flaky salt on top… perfection. 🤌🏻
Notes: *Pro tip: these actually turn out PERFECT if they're frozen and baked directly from frozen. You'll have to let them cook a little longer, but they're sooooo good. I tend to just make the batter and freeze like 80% so I always have cookies on hand.

ingredients.Name: Pie Crust, rolled out (either homemade, pie scraps, or bought!)
apples, thinly sliced (any kind, new, old, whatever you have!)
sugar, plus 2 tbsp (cane, white granulated, brown, coconut, whatever makes you happy)

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 375F and place a rack in the center of the oven.
Place pie crust on a rimmed baking sheet lined with parchment. Place back in the fridge to keep it chilled.
Combine all ingredients in a large bowl (EXCEPT 1 tbsp heavy cream and 2 extra tbsp sugar)

Dump apple mixture in the center of the pie crust. Gently pull the edges of the pie crust towards the center, but not totally to the middle. It doesn’t need to be pretty and the crust will naturally fold over itself as you work around the pie. That is all good!
Use a pastry brush to coat the exposed pie crust and sprinkle the last 2 tbsp sugar on top. This will add a little extra crunch and sparkle.

Bake for 60-75 minutes, turning half way to cook evenly. You're looking for the crust to be golden, crispy, and apples soft/softening. If you have old apples like me they may not turn super mushy, but embrace the ingredients you have!!
Let cool and top with a big ol’ scoop of vanilla ice cream!
Enjoy!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Apple Galette n’ Ice Cream
Description:
A galette is perfect for using up “not perfect” ingredients because, well… it’s meant to not be perfect. It’s rustic. It’s messy. It’s easy peasy and one of the bestest things. And somehow it is like seriously impressive. 

The apples were dry and sad, the bag of pie scraps really needed to be eaten, but hey a beautiful dessert was born. 💃

Pie crust was still flaky and crispy which… considering the whole being frozen in scraps and put back together thing, that’s a major compliment to my pie crust recipe/method. 

Remember everything doesn’t have to be absotootly perfect in order to make something stunning. Embrace what you have. ❤️

ingredients.Name: For The Passion Fruit Sauceyyy Sauce
VERY ripe passion fruit, innards removed. They’re good when they’re SUPER wrinkly.
A couple strips of lemon peel

directions.Direction: For The Passion Fruit Sauceyyy Sauce

Put passion fruit flesh in a large, fine mesh strainer and using a spoon smoosh it down to break up all of the fibrous bits. It’s going to take awhile, but just believe in the process. Add your lemon juice on top and repeat the smooshing process. The lemon juice will help break it down. Then repeat with maple syrup.

At this point you should really only have seeds left in your strainer… dump those in! Yes, you did all that work to separate it but we DO want the seeds for texture. Just trust me here. Add your pinch o’ salt and you’re good boo.
This can be done a couple days prior.
For The Panna Cotta
Add milk to a small bowl and sprinkle gelatin on top, set aside.

Combine the remaining milk, cream, sugar, lemon peels, vanilla extract, and salt in a medium pot. Cook over medium heat until it is simmering. Remove from the heat, remove the lemon peels, and slowly whisk in the gelatin mixture. Once mixed, bring back to the stove and heat for one more minute but do not let it boil.
Skim off any bubbles that are on the top, seems extra but just do it.
Pour into 6 lil cups, tea cups, or ramekins. It doesn’t really matter just try to get them all even.
Place in the fridge IDEALLY overnight, but seriously at least like 7 hours.
Once they’ve properly chilled, run a knife along the edges and invert onto a plate. Spoon a couple tablespoons of sauce on top and ENJOY.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: PASSION FRUIT Panna Cotta
Description: Went to La Natural in Miami a couple months ago, got this dessert, and HAD to attempt to recreate it. Dis is what I did.

ingredients.Name: ghee or coconut oil (room temp not melted), plus more to prep the cookie sheet
Approximately  in knob of ginger, grated

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 325F and prepare your baking sheet. I personally use a cast iron baking sheet and just slather ghee all over it. It’s perfectly non-stick and you’re actually getting some added iron ;)
Use a whisk to combine the dry ingredients in a large bowl, mixie mix, and set aside.
Use dat same whisk to thoroughly mix all of the wet ingredients in a separate bowl.
Once mixed, pour the wet into the dry and whisk together. Once whisking doesn’t work just switch to a flexible spatula or wooden spoon to fully incorporate.

Use a cookie cutter to measure out approximately 1.5 tbsp portions. You should have 8 cookies in total if you just want to eyeball it! The dough is pretty firm so it shouldn't be that hard really. Just divide in half, then in half again, and then those in half. Done!

Roll them into neat little ballz, evenly space them on your baking sheet, then use a fork to gently smoosh them making a criss cross pattern. They don’t really spread in the oven so this is what will give them their cookie shape.

Bake at 325F for 18-22 minutes. We want a little lower and slower to let them crisp up a bit. Since they’re already brown you can’t really go by “browning” to determine their doneness. Instead you want to see crisping on the outside edges and even on top, I just touch the top of the cookie to see if we got some crisping. You also want it to feel firm-ish to the touch. If it smooshes totally down, that sucks, and just give it 2 more minutes at a time.
Cool on a wire rack and
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: HEALTHY Molasses Ginger Cookiez
Description:
No seriously, they’re like actually good for you. 
Grain free, sugar free, and *almost* dairy free… I mean it can be dairy free if you just sub the ghee for coconut oil which is totally cool with me. 😘

They’re filled with so much goodness you can even feel guilt free eating these with coffee in the morning. 

It’s everything I want in a ginger molasses cookie AND MORE. They’re so easy to make… just give it a go. Seriously.

ingredients.Name: bread flour, plus more for dusting

directions.Direction: Begin your autolyse by combining both flours and water. I like to knead the mixture for about 1 minute to ensure that there is no pesky unincorporated flour remaining. Make sure you're checking the bottom of the bowl as it likes to hide there! If you don't fully incorporate the flour at this point you will have blobs of thick bits throughout the entire process. So while the dough can look shaggy you DON'T want dry/floury. 60 seconds of kneading should do the trick.
Mix in 70g starter and knead for about 2 minutes. I like to do a combination of stretch and folds and the rubaud method.

Then sprinkle the salt over the top of the dough and add the additional 1 tsp of water to help dilute it. The dough will probably start to come apart here, but that's ok! Just keep kneading or doing the rubaud method for about 2 more minutes and it should come together in a smooth ball. *You don't want to over knead here!!!* Once the dough looks like it's together and is smoothish, you're done.
Cover the bowl and leave it at room temp and out of direct sunlight for 1 hour.

After the hour you're going to perform your first round of stretch and folds. Think of the dough and bowl as being four quadrants. Wet your hand and gently slip it along the bowl and under the dough at the top 1/4 quadrant. Lift the dough up (stretch) and lay it back down over the center of the dough (fold). Turn the bowl 90 degrees and repeat 3 times; aka 4 times in total. Cover the bowl and let sit for another hour.
Repeat the stretching and folding four times in total.

After the 4th stretch and fold it's time for the dough to just hang out and proof! Depending on the temperature of your home this could take anywhere from 2-5 extra hours. You want the dough to have doubled in size from its original volume and be jiggly when you gently shake the bowl. Focus more on the visuals than the time on the clock.
Dust the top of the dough with flour and lightly flour a clean work surface. Gently turn out the dough onto the work surface, flour side down obviously.

Time to pre-shape. Gently stretch the dough in all directions just to even the thickness out (it's better to stretch LESS than more). Then take the left quadrant, lift it, and fold it over to the center of the dough. Repeat with the right side, so now it's a log-ish shape. Then fold bottom top center and sort of flip it onto the top portion. So now what was just on the counter should be face up.
Use your bench scraper and tension off the counter to sort of tighten the ball. Cover and allow to rest for 10 minutes. Prepare your banneton.

Gently flour the top of the dough once again and flip it over. So back to flour side down! Stretch it again and repeat the same folding process on the left and right side. But this time instead of just folding the top and bottom we're going to roll it like a jelly roll. Pinch and tuck the side edges so that all seams are under the log now.

Gently lift and place the dough into the banneton, seam side up!! I typically create even more tension by stitching the dough, but you can absolutely stop here if you're not comfortable with that. But if you want to, I "stitch" by grabbing a small portion of either side of the dough, bring it to the center and slightly past that, overlapping the opposite side. Then almost like twist them together. Then continue that motion up the entire length of the dough. By the end of it, it should look like a creep lil stitch.

Dust with flour once more, cover, and allow to rest for another 1-3 hours. This is a tricky time to rest because it's already quite proofed and is now covered in flour. My suggestion is go for 1 hour and then eventually you'll learn your dough and what it "should" feel and look like. You can always do the poke test to gauge its rise!
Place in the refrigerator overnight; about 12ish hours.
Preheat the oven and dutch oven at 450F.

Once preheated I begin getting the bread ready! To do so I take a narrow and long piece of parchment paper, cover the dough so that the longer ends of parchment are on the sides (not top and bottom) of the banneton. Then I hold tension on the parchment and turn the banneton/dough over. This just helps the dough from dropping down onto the counter and potentially losing bubbles.

I like to dust the top with flour once more, give it a lil rub with my hand, then brush off the excess flour from the dough and parchment. Use a lame or sharp knife to score the top. If you haven't done this before I suggest just one long score.

Then use the parchment "handles" to lift the dough and place in the preheated dutch oven. Place the lid of the dutch oven on top and bake for 25 minutes at 450F covered. After 25 minutes remove the lid, lower the temp to 425F and continue to cook for 15 minutes for a thin and light crust, 20 minutes for a thicker and more robust rust, and 25 minutes for a deeply golden and dense crust.
Allow to FULLY COOL prior to cutting in and guess what. That's it...
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Baby Einkorn Sourdough Loaf
Description:
Ok ok it's not actually baby sized, but it's definitely smaller than the OTHER Einkorn loaf recipe. And I'll be honest with you... I'm using "einkorn" in the title liberally because it has a higher proportion of bread flour than einkorn flour. 
But alas! The einkorn is what really drives this recipe and well earns the title.

I hope you love it.

* STEP 3: Einkorn doesn't have the same protein structure as a traditional flour, so you don't want to over knead and break those bonds.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Big Einkorn Sourdough Loafs
Description:
This recipe has essentially the same proportions as my "baby einkorn sourdough loaf", but this time we're 1. increasing the size and 2. doubling the recipe! 

So if the baby loaf is perfect for say a house of 2, this would be a bit more substantial! Or if you just eat a lot of bread then this is the recipe for you!! 

I love the size of the slices that this recipe makes and it's perrrrfect for sandwiches. 

You can always freeze the second loaf after you bake it! So the same amount of work, but twice the amount of sourdough enjoyment.
Notes: * this recipe calls for more starter than the "baby sourdough" loaf. To make sure you have enough starter you can opt to double the feeding ratio (20x60x60 will turn into 40 grams starter, 120 grams water, 120 grams bread flour). OR You can opt to feed the starter with a slightly high food to starter ratio (25 grams starter, 100 grams water, 100 grams bread flour) but I'd recommend doing that about 2-3 days prior to baking to ensure that the starter has time to adjust.

ingredients.Name: room temp unsalted butter, cut into tbsp pieces

directions.Direction: Add all hazelnuts to a food processor and pulse until they are super finely ground. Don’t go so far that you’re making a nut butter, but you want it prettttty fine. (I probably should’ve went farther in my video, but even with some small chunks the cookies are still beautiful!) Separate the mixture in half (2/3 cup each) and set both bowls to the side.

Add the butter and powdered sugar to the food process - don’t worry about cleaning it! Let that spin until the butter and sugar are combined, light, and smooth. (Scraping down the sides as you go to make sure everything incorporates)
Add the yolks and vanilla extract. Mixie mix until it incorporates again. Thennnn add flour and salt, mixie mix until a stiff dough forms.
Take 2/3 of the dough and put it in a separate bowl. Add the almond flour to that bowl and mixie until the mixture is smooth and fully incorporated.

You an either use 2 sheets of parchment or plastic wrap (parchment is easier but in a pickle plastic will work… like I did!) Work the dough between the two pieces so you get an even rectangle that’s 12 x 8 inches. I use a firm bench scraper to help me mold and scrape it into shape! Put on a baking sheet (or directly down on a flat surface in the fridge) and chill for 10-15 minutes. You want it firm but pliable.
While that’s chilling, add cocoa powder and 2/3 cup ground hazelnuts (1 bowl) to the remaining dough left in the food processor. Mixie mix until everything is fully incorporated.

Once the dough slab in the fridge is sufficiently chilled, plop the chocolate hazelnut mix over top. Use an offset spatula or spoon to evenly spread the mixture over the top of the dough. You want to leave a 1/2 in boarder along the longer sides, but go all the way to the end on the short sides.

Use the parchment/plastic wrap to help you do it, but roll up the dough into a tight log - longways/hotdog roll! Wrap the dough in the parchment/plastic wrap and chill for AT LEAST an hour, but up to 2 days.
Arrange the oven racks on the top and bottom 1/3 of the oven. Preheat to 350F. Prepare baking 2 baking sheets with parchment (or if you don’t have any a light coating of oil)
Cut the dough into 32 pieces by cutting it in half (soft of rolling the log with you as you cut so you don’t compress it flat anywhere) then in half again, then in half again, then in fourths!

Place all the cookies rounds on the prepared baking sheets and bake for a total of 15-20 minutes, rotating and switching the racks half way through. You want to bake until the edges are starting to get golden. Cool completely on the baking sheet!
Once cool, melt chocolate chips over a double boiler or in the microwave. While that’s melting, combine the other 2/3 cup hazelnuts and turbinado sugar.

Working one cookie at a time, roll the edges of the cookie in the melted chocolate and then immediately into the sugar hazelnut mixture. Place on a baking sheet to firm up. Repeat with all of the cookies! Once everything is rolled I suggest letting it fully firm up in the fridge.
Once the chocolate is set you can leave these at room temp! They will keep up to 5 days at room temp in an airtight container.
ENJOY!

Name: Chocolate Hazelnut Pinwheels
Description:
My mother deemed these “the best cookies she has ever had” so you know it’s true 😘
But seriously they are like really up there for the best cookies I’ve ever had. 

And best part, they look soooo much more complex than they actually are!
So if you don’t feel like being healthy and bringing my Dates on Crack to your cookies swap, bring these!! 🔥

The chocolate and hazelnut is the perfect combo 👏🏻
Not too sweet, give you that chocolate fix, and are a total show stopper!

Recipe adapted from Clair Saffitz’s Pistachio Pinwheels in Dessert Person

ingredients.Name: Animal fat or other oil for frying
vanilla bean paste or vanilla extract

directions.Direction: Heat oil in a medium sized pot so that you have at least 2 in of oil.
To a large bowl, add starter, egg, ricotta, vanilla, and maple syrup. Mixie mix to combine.
Add in flour, baking powder, salt, and mixie mix once again until a smooth batter forms.

Use a 2 1/2 tbsp cookie scoop (or a big ol tablespoon and hefty scoops) to scoop out batter. You want to fill 1/2 or 3/4 of the cookie scoop with batter, add 1/4 - 1/2 tsp jelly, then cover that with more batter.
Plot batter into oil and fry for about 2-4 minutes on each side. You want golden and crispyyyy!!
Sprinkle and dust with powdered sugar annnndddd

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Jelly Filled Donut Holes
Description:
It’s a rainy, lazy Sunday and I’m committed to chillin on the couch today. 👏🏻 
HOWEVER. I started craving donuts…. 🍩

And if you know me I’m not going out to buy donuts, I’m MAKING donuts! 

But I also didn’t want to put in all the effort of rolling out dough and waiting on fermentation, so I went for these quick DONUT HOLEZZZZZ ❤️‍🔥
