Adapted from a recipe by Angela Lynne

ingredients.Name: vanilla extract or vanilla bean paste

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 350F and prep 12 muffin tins. I use cast iron muffin tins. You can spray with coconut oil or brush on olive oil or butter.
Add bananas to a large bowl and mash until they are a thick paste. Add in the other wet ingredients and mix to combine.
In a separate bowl, whisk to combine the dry ingredients.
Add the dry ingredients to the wet and mix until just combined.
Use a rolling pin or knife to break up the chocolate bar into chip sized pieces. Keep about 4 tbsp reserved. Add the remaining chocolate to the batter and mix again to combine.
Use a 1/4 measuring cup to spoon batter into the prepped muffin tins. You may have some batter leftover so just fill every tin up to 3/4 full. Top with the reserved chocolate pieces.
Bake at 350F for 20-24 minutes or until a toothpick comes out mostly dry. It may still be a taddddd wet because they're moist muffins, but you don't want globs of raw batter.
Let the muffins cool in their tins, then once easy to handle transfer them to cool fully on a wire rack or plate.
I personally like them best toasted with some extra butter, but they're delicious just on their own.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Banana Almond Sourdough Muffins
Description: While creating these muffins I thought I was soooo clever. Like whoa these are gluten free, can easily be dairy free, refined sugar free… and then I realized that they have sourdough starter in them and sourdough starter is very much not gluten free. Though the other two still stand! I use whole milk which can easily be subbed for plant AND there is olive oil in place of butter. They also only have ¼ cup of sweetener and I used maple syrup to keep them refined sugar free. We use almond flour/meal in place of more wheat flour which makes them protein filled and easy to digest!

directions.Direction: To a large bowl at 350g flour, salt, and sugar. Place in the fridge while you prep the butter.

Use a bench scraper or knife to cut the butter. First lengthwise (hotdog), then flip 90 degrees and cut lengthwise (hotdog) again, then cut into 1/2 in cubes width wise. Repeat with the other stick of butter.
Plop all of the butter pieces into the flour mixture and toss to coat in the flour. You want to break up the butter cubes so every single piece gets fully coated in flour.

Next, gather all of the butter pieces towards one side of the bowl and taking one piece (or one in each hand) at a time, smoosh the butter cube between your thumb, index, and middle fingers. Then plop it over on the other side of the bowl. This just helps you see what has and has not been smooshed yet. Once everything is smooshed just toss to coat in the flour once again.

If you want an insanely flaky crust, think like rough puff pastry, you can stop here, but if you just want reasonable flakiness we’re going to break down those pieces even farther. Just rub the butter and flour between your fingers until the largest pieces are the size of about a walnut. If you want a shorter crust you can keep processing until the mixture resembles more like a thick sand.

Pour in the majority of your ice water into the mixture and toss everything around to incorporate. Watch out for big clumpy bits right off the bat and break those up. Sort of toss and knead for about 20 seconds, then test the hydration by squeezing a mound of dough between your hands - if it holds together it’s hydrated, if it breaks apart very easily it needs more water. If a section is hydrated just put it over to the side on the counter, and continue with the remaining mixture, adding more water little by little, until everything is hydrated and holding together. *You don’t want a soupy mess!!!! Depending on your flour you may need to add more water, just do 1 tbsp at a time.

Once everything is hydrated, gather it all on the counter/work surface and compress into a rectangle. Lightly dust with flour and roll out to about double the length. Then letter fold by taking the top 1/3 and folding it to the center and repeating with the bottom 1/3. Rotate 90 degrees and repeat the letter fold process. It should be holding together pretty well by this point!
Cut the dough in half and wrap both in plastic wrap. Make sure to sort of compress the dough into the edges of the plastic wrap to smooth it out and just further incorporate it.
Refrigerate for AT LEAST 30 minutes, but up to 3 days.
At this point you’re ready to move forward using the dough however the recipe requires! If you’re making the apple hand pies, continue to the next two steps.

Flour your work surface, rolling pin, and dough, and roll it out to an approximately 10 x 12 in rectangle. Make sure to add more flour, flip, and rotate the dough as you roll it out. You can also use your bench scraper to help encourage the dough into a rectangular shape.

Use a ruler to cut the sheet into 8 rectangles. To do so, cut the dough in half width wise (hamburger) and in quarters length wise (hot dog). It’s ok if the edges aren’t fully straight. Repeat with the other dough.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: THE Flaky Pie Crust
Description:
It is THE pie crust recipe. It combines a couple techniques, but once you get the hang of it you will literally never buy pie crust ever again. 

Depending on how finely you process the butter you can achieve a variety of different flaky/tenderness levels all from one dough! 

The sugar not only adds some flavor, but helps encourage browning. However, you can ABSOLUTELY omit it.

ingredients.Name: all purpose flour, plus a sprinkle more for flouring the work surface
salt, plus more for sprinkling the tops
whole milk, plus more for topping

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 425F.
Mix flour, baking powder, salt, and sugar in a large bowl. Add grated butter and mash with your hands until a slightly sandy texture comes together.

Add the grated cheddar cheese and scallions and toss to coat. Next add the whole milk. Use your hands or a wooden spoon to combine until no dry flour remains. I like to use my hands so I can sort of knead the dough.

Dump out onto a lightly floured surface, form into a mound, and roll out into a 1/2-3/4 in thick patty. (1/2in will yield 12 thinner biscuits and 3/4in will 9 thicker biscuits.) Use an approximately 3 in cookie cutter to cut the dough into biscuit size rounds. You can also use a cup or an aluminum can with its contents removed. Stamp out as many biscuits as you can in the first round and then form and stamp out until all of the dough is used.
Place on a baking sheet, no need to oil the surface but if you want you can smear some butter on the pan. Brush with a tinyyyyy bit of extra milk!
Bake at 425F for 15-20 minutes. Until the tops are golden and biscuits are puffed.
Ideally wait a couple minutes until cutting into them, but honestly I never can so just dive right in.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Cheddar Scallion Biscuits
Description:
These are the BEST biscuits I have ever had, and coming from someone from the south that is saying A LOT. They're shockingly tender and moist while somehow still staying together perfectly. Also they're not outrageously huge so it doesn't feel like carbo overload. The balance between the scallions, cheddar, and slightly sweet biscuit is truly a match made in heaven. Top it with a jammy egg, bacon, and some extra cheddar cheese and you are set. 

PS you can EASILY double this recipe, which frankly I highly recommend because I got through these like hot cakes. Or hot biscuits 😘
Notes:
* For years we used an aluminum can with both the top and bottom cut out... it works just fine.
*Lately I've been making these thicker and bigger! It yields about 6 biscuits with the FULL recipe. So play around, see what thickness and diameter you like best :)

ingredients.Name: all spice (you can also sub with cinnamon or cardamon)

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 375F with the rack in the center of the oven.

In a large bowl combine the plums, brown sugar, cornstarch, lemon juice, vanilla, and salt in a large bowl. Add to whatever baking dish you're baking it in. You want the filling to come up to the top of the baking dish since it will lose a little bit of height while cooking.

Grab a medium sized bowl to prepare the crumb topping. First combine the dry ingredients: all purpose flour, almond meal, brown sugar, baking powder, all spice, and salt. Then add in the coconut oil and coconut milk. At first it'll seem like the mixture is a bit too runny to be a crumb, and then with about 20 seconds of whisking you'll see it thicken right up.
Plop tablespoon sized dollops of crumb topping all over the top of the plum filling. Sprinkle the raw sugar on top of the crumb.
Place on a rimmed baking sheet and pop in the oven at 375F. Bake for 30-40 minutes - until the crumb topping is golden and the plum filling is bubbling.
Let cool slightly before serving. Top with vanilla ice cream (you can keep it dairy free or use whatever kind of vanilla ice cream you like).
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Dairy Free Plum Cobbler
Description:
~technically it’s vegan~ but you'd literally never know. 

Going in my parent’s backyard and harvesting plums off of their plum tree was such a dreamy experience. ✨

I wanted to make something summery, easy, and nostalgic. QUE: Plum Cobbler. 

I abide by the “barely sweet” approach in my desserts so if you don’t like getting smacked in the face with glucose every time you want to “indulge”, than this and all of my dessert recipes are for you. 

I created this recipe for my sister who is totally dairy free, but if you want to sub the coconut oil and coconut milk with butter and regular milk than more power to you! 😘

But between the coconut oil, coconut milk, and almond meal, this is bringing all the wonderful flavors you are craving yet don't typically find in tradish cobbler.
Notes:
*You can sub out the plums for any stone fruit you can get your hands on!
*Since the plums are so tart you really do need vanilla ice cream as the topping (which I factored that additional sweetness in while making this recipe). So if you're forgoing the vanilla ice cream (WHY?!) than I recommend doubling the sugar in the plum filling.

ingredients.Name: prepared pie crust my flaky pie crust is linked!
plums, pits removed and cut into bite sized pieces

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 375F with the rack in the middle of the oven.

If you are using the homemade pie crust recipe, use 1 pie doughs worth of dough and roll out into a 12in circle. It doesn't have to be perfect! If you're using store-bought just cut it into a 12in circle.
Place the dough on a rimmed baking sheet. (I used 18x12in)
In a small bowl combine the brown sugar, almond extract, and cardamon.
To the center of the crust add the flour and almond meal. Spread that evenly leaving a 1 inch border around the edges. Then add 1/2 of the brown sugar mixture.
Top that with your plums, followed by the remaining 1/2 of the brown sugar mixture.
Gently fold the excess dough towards the center of the crust and over the plums. You're essentially tucking in the plums and building a "crust".
Brush the "crust" portion of the dough with the beaten egg and sprinkle on some turbinado sugar.
Bake at 375F for 45-55 minutes. You want the crust browned and crisp and the plums tender and juicy. Let cool before slicing if you don't want a plum juice waterfall!
Top with vanilla ice cream and
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: PLUM GALETTE aka Pie's Lazy Rustic Chic Sister
Description:
I will forever be team galette vs. pie for its total unfussiness. Like everything you love about pie and nothing you hate? Yeah sign me up. 

This bad boy should come with a warning sign because you WILL find yourself wanting to eat it every single chance you get. Which hey, I guess that’s your warning.

ingredients.Name: cold butter, cut into small pieces cubes
fresh pitted cherries (no need to chop further)

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 400F
Whisk to combine flour, almond meal, baking powder, baking soda, cardamon, and salt in a large bowl. Set aside.

Cut the butter into cubes by cutting it length wise (hotdog), then turning it 90 degrees so the cut side is now on the side, cutting again length wise, then cutting width wise in 1/4 in cube widths. So basically you should be left with a ton of little butter cubes that are all even in size.
Add the butter to the dry ingredients and use your fingers/hands to break it down until the mixture has a sandy like texture.
In another bowl whisk to combine the egg, milk, yogurt, maple syrup, and almond extract.
Add the wet ingredients to the dry ingredients and use a spatula to combine.
Once it starts coming together add in the cherries, walnuts, and mini chocolate chips. Stir until evenly distributed... but only until just then! Don't over mix.
Pour onto a clean work surface, form into a mound, and roll into a 12ish inch round circle.
Use a knife or bench scraper to cut into 12 even pizza shaped slices. (you can go bigger, you'll just need to bake them for longer and at 375F)
Place on a lightly oiled baking sheet, top with a couple more chocolate chips if you have them, and bake at 400F for 12-16 minutes. You want puffed up and golden!
Let cool for a couple minutes on the pan and then transfer to a wire rack to finish cooling.
ENJOY! (pro tip, dunk it in some milk!)

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Sugar Free Chocolate Cherry Walnut Scones
Description:
If you've been following along for awhile than you know I like my desserts barely sweet. These scones are the perfect example that you can have a sweet and delicious treat without being blassssted with sugar. 

They're lightly sweetened with maple syrup (just 2 tbsp in 12 scones!!!) and get the majority of their sweetness naturally from the cherries and a little boost from the chocolate chips. 
In my opinion they're not only "lightly sweetened", but "perfectly sweetened". 

Also, typically scones are sort of tough... these are NOT that. We utilize almond meal and yogurt to bring a super light and tender scone-y texture.
Notes:
* The easiest way to remove the pit from the cherry: 1. place on a cutting board 2. position knife so it lines up with the stem and butt of the cherry 3. begin cutting at a bias until your knife grazes the pit 4. start rolling and slicing, keeping the knife positioned right against the pit 5. once all of the center flesh is removed you can chop of the tiny bits at the stem and butt ends
* Measure the yogurt by first pouring the milk into your liquid measuring cup, then adding enough yogurt to increase the total volume by 1/4 cup

ingredients.Name: medjool dates, pitted (you use any date that you have!)

directions.Direction: Pry open the dates so you have ample filling space.
Use a spoon to smoosh peanut butter into the center of the date and smooth it out.

Melt chocolate chips and coconut oil in the microwave for about 30 seconds. Give it a stir and then microwave one more time for about 10 seconds. There should still be some chunks of chocolate, but the residual heat of the melted chocolate will continue to melt those bits. If not, just give it another 10-30 seconds.

Plop a date in the chocolate mix, make sure it’s all coated, all the excess chocolate to stream down, then place on a plate or wire rack. Repeat with all of the dates. Place in the freezer to quickly chill/firm the chocolate. Once hard repeat the dipping! Do the dipping process 2 more times, for a total of 3 choco dunks! *A fork works best for letting the excess chocolate drip down.
On the last dunk sprinkle the tops with some flaky salt. Then just chill one last time in the freezer or fridge annnnd
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: PB + Choco Datez
Description:
These peanut butter filled, dark chocolate dipped datez are absolutely bonkerz.
I kid you not I could eat the entire tray in one day. 

I mean sweet dates + dark chocolate + peanut butter + flaky salt…

ingredients.Name: Chex wheat if you also want to pretend to be healthy
peanut butter clearly doesn’t matter at all if it’s creamy or crunchy
unsalted butter honestly salted would be fine
72% chocolate chips a standard bag is 10oz which would be better buttttt, I already used some
Like  Trader Joes dark chocolate peanut butter because once again…

directions.Direction: Alright y’all. Pour your Chex into a big ass bowl and set aside. Get your desired pan (I used a 9x9 glass pyrex but literally anything is fine) and coat it in oil… We all know I used ghee.
Combine marshmallows, peanut butter, and butter in a pot and cook that on low to medium-low, stirring frequently until it is melted. To make this easy as possible have the butter on the bottom.
Pour that marshmallow mix over your Chex and do your damndest to mix it up. It’s tough, just believe.

Pour dat into your prepped pan and encourage it to smoosh down. Don’t use all of the force you have or else it’ll get too dense, but trust it’ll still be yummy if you’re just that strong. Set aside for uno momento.

Add chocolate and coconut oil to a a microwave safe bowl and blast for 20 second intervals, stirring in between, until melted. Pour over your Chex crispiez. Move the pan around if you’re like me and it didn’t want to cooperate. Sprinkle with flaky salt.
Let it firm up (me: freezer because i’m impatient) and then slice those babies uppppp. These are delish breakfast, lunch, and dinner.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Chocolate Peanut Butter Chex CRISPIEZ
Description:
For when those munchies are hitting. 

This is hardly even a recipe because I tested nothing and threw stuff in a pan and it was PHENOM.
But alas, this is how I did it.

First of all, these aren’t made with RICE Crispies. NO, That’s boring. These have CHEX cause they’re crunchy AF and made with whole wheat which gives them an even nuttier flavor, and plus it helps me pretend it’s healthy.

directions.Direction: Preheat the oven to 350F.
Prick some holes all over the sweet potatoes and bake for 45-60 minutes, or until soft. You can also sub for canned sweet potato here, you’d need about 1.5 cans. BUT fresh is always best if you can.
Let those to cool slightly before handling and removing the skin.
Add sweet potatoes, 1/2 cup cream, 1/4 cup maple syrup, pinch of salt, and 1 tsp cinnamon to a blender. Blend until smooth and scrape down the sides.
Add the 2 eggs and blend just until combined.
Divide into either 2 14oz ramekins or 4-6 7oz.
If you have the larger ramekins bake at 350F for 45-60 minutes. If you have the smaller ramekins bake at 350F for 25-30 minutes.
Orrrrr until slightly browned, crinkly and the center is set when you jiggle it.
Let cool and make the whipped cream.
Pour the other 1/2 cup heavy in a medium sized bowl and whisk until soft peaks form.
Then add the 1 tbsp maple syrup and mixie mix once again.
Topped your cooled sweet potato custard with whipped cream, garnish with some extra cinnamon, and
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Sweet Potato Custard n’ Whipped Cream
Description:
A perfect lil’ sweet potato custard with homemade whipped cream. 👼🏻

For those days when you want a decadent, Fall flavored sweet treat, but don’t want to spend hours doing it. 

It’s sooo easy to throw together, nutrient dense (packed full of protein and vitamin A), and perfectly portioned.

ingredients.Name: pie crusts (homemade or store bought is fine)
crisp apples, cut into 1 cm cubes
apple cider, the juice NOT the vinegar

directions.Direction: If you’re using premade pie dough just skip to the part where you start cutting it up. (TO MAKE THE PIE CRUST SCROLL DOWN TO STEPS 11 & 12 of the "THE Flaky Pie Crust" recipe!)

In a medium pot, combine butter, apples, lemon zest, lemon juice, apple cider, light brown sugar, cinnamon, and vanilla. Let that simmer over medium-low for 20-30 minutes, or until the apples are very softened and liquid has reduced in half.
Pour out a couple tablespoons of the liquid into a separate bowl and add the cornstarch. Use a whisk to mix together.
Add the cornstarch mix back to the pot and reduce the heat to low. Stir for about 1 minute or until the liquid thickens up significantly. Let that cool COMPLETELY before assembling the hand pies.
While cooling, combine the egg and water and whisk until no streaks remain. Set aside.
Preheat oven to 425F and ideally have a baking stone in there to preheat as well.
Once cooled, place 8 pie crust rectangles on a parchment lined baking sheet and add 3ish tablespoons to the center of the 8 rectangles. Leave at least a 1/2 in boarder around the edges.
Brush a thin layer of egg wash around the 1/2 in pie crust boarder.

Use the remaining 8 pie rectangles and place on top of the apple mixture. I like to match shapes of rectangles, so like if one is straight on all edges except the top right corner is curved, I’ll match those. Ya feel me?
Gently press the two pieces of pie crust together to form a seal around the apple mixture.

Use your bench scraper to cut away excess, untidy pie crust, so you’re left with 4 straight edges and right angles. This will also help adhere the two pieces together. Make sure you’re leaving some space between the cut and the apple filling though!!! Just cut away unnecessary dough and try to make all 8 pies similar sizes.
Then use a fork and gently press all of the edges to add some flare AND once again pressing the two pieces together. We don’t want any leakage here!!!
Brush all 8 hand pies with the egg wash, doing your best to avoid getting it on the parchment.
Coat evenly with the turbinado sugar and cut at least 1 hole in the top of each pie. I prefer three little slits, but that’s just me!

Place the baking sheet on top of the baking stone, if using, close the oven door and immediately lower the temp to 375F. Bake for 24-32 minutes, or until golden and crispy! My oven is all over the place so I’m offering you a wide range of time. Your biggest cue is the visual!!! You want golden on top to ensure that the bottom is nice and crisp! No soggy bottoms here.
Let cool on a wire rack and
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: McDonalds Copy Cat Apple Hand Pie
Description:
Bring on all the Fall feelz with this deeeelicious Apple Hand Pie. 

Flaky crust and sweet, lemony, cinnamon-y apples all in a handheld lil pie. What more could you ask for?!

While it may look intense, this recipe is actually quite easy! And made even easier if you just buy some premade dough! (But I promise the homemade stuff is so so so good) 

*We need 2 sheets of pie dough*

I personally like to start the dough, then while that is resting I make the apple filling, then while that is chilling I like to cut the dough, then fill etc etc. You get the idea! But you can absolutely fully prep the dough prior to making the apple filling.

ingredients.Name: Medjool Dates cut in half (so 30 halves)
nut butter, give or take. (Peanut works best, but other nuts reduce your potential exposure to mold so we've been doing pecan butter)
nuts. I like Brazil nuts best, but pecan, walnuts, pistachios, or peanuts all work great!

directions.Direction: Begin by filling each date with a little bit of nut butter. You don't want it oozing out here.
Top each date half with one nut. Pop them all in the freezer to harden while we melt our chocolate.

Using a double boiler (aka just a pot filled with a tinnnnny bit of water set over simmer and another heat proof bowl set over that but not touching the water) melt your chocolate. You can stir occasionally to help it all melt. You can remove it from the heat when you just have a couple of tiny chocolate pieces left, the residual heat will melt those.
If you want a thin coating of chocolate you can just start dunking now. If you want a thicker coating of chocolate let the chocolate sit for 3 minutes.
Use a fork to dunk and coat each date bite. I like to scrape the bottom of the date on the side of the bowl to remove excess chocolate from the bottom. Repeat until all date pieces are coated.
Let them sit for another 3ish minutes THEN top with some flaky salt. I like a lot of salt personally! The mix of the sweet date and dark chocolate can really stand up to it!
If you're in a rush pop them in the freezer to set, otherwise you can just put them in the fridge.
While they won't melt at room temperature, they are most stable if stored in the fridge. So keep them in an airtight container in the fridge until you're ready to serve them.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Dates on Crack
Description:
Ditch the cookies this year and bring these chocately date bites to your cookie swap instead.

Imagine this. It’s 1 hour before your cookie swap party and you DIDN’T MAKE ANY COOKIES. The horrors. Anxiety strikes. Fear kicks in! What do you do??? 

Ok it’s not that serious and even if you do REMEMBER to make something for your cookie swap, give these a try. 

*I literally have these written out as “dates on crack”. So that should tell you how good and addicting they are!*

They’re like the most perfect lil chocolate candy bar you’ve ever had, but they’re good for you. Weird concept. 👼🏻

I always do 1/2 a date as the base, some nut butter (and we’ve been loving the Abbys Better pecan butter), a nut (I loveeeee Brazil nuts here cuz crunch n’ selenium 👸🏼), dip that puppy in some DARK chocolate, and sprinkle with flaky salt. 

They’re so good and everyone will be thanking you for a healthy alternative. 👏🏻

or just do what Daniel and I do and crush like 10 a night on your own. 😘
Notes: These really only take a couple minutes to throw together, but you need to let them chill in the fridge or freezer so that takes a little while.

directions.Direction: Add carrots and walnuts to a food processor. Pulse and blend until the carrots are finely chopped. Then while the mixer is going, stream in the maple syrup. Stop the mixer and add the cinnamon and maple syrup. Mix again until the carrots and walnuts are finely chopped and everything is coming together.
Set aside and quickly rinse out the mixer.
Add heavy cream, cream cheese, and maple syrup to the mixer and blend until thick and fully whipped.
Crush 3-4 cookies and set aside.

To assemble add cream to the bottom of the bowl, layer with cookies, then another layer of whipped cream. Moving forward the layers will be cream, carrot filling, cookie. Repeat until the final layer of whipped cream is on top. I like to use two different rubber spatulas to help keep the layers distinct. Top cake with your crushed cookies and a sprinkle of cinnamon.
Cover and refrigerate at least 6 hours, but ideally overnight.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Carrot Icebox Cake
Description:
The final day of my Easter Series! 

I knew I had to make a dessert, but I just wasn’t going to make a traditional carrot cake. I kept passing these ginger cookies at Trader Joe’s (you can use any ginger cookie you have access to) and just knew there was something there.

My mind instantly went to those icebox cakes that my grandmother used to make. Icebox cakes are perfect since they are fully assembled the day before - freeing up precious time the day of!

Utilizing a carrot walnut filling (only sweetened with maple syrup!) was a no brainer to make this icebox cake a carrot cake!

The whipped cream has tons of texture and carrot cake flavor thanks to the whole block of cream cheese we use. 

It’s everything you want in a carrot cake, but with like 20% of the effort.

I utilized a food processor to make my life even easier, but if you don't have one you can still do this all by hand!

ingredients.Name: coconut cream (try to find BPA free lined cans)
bag chocolate chips (go with bittersweet if you can, the higher the % the better!)
nut butter (almond, peanut, pistachio, tahini, cashew, macadamia, or a mix of whatever you like!)
Other optional add ins: chopped walnuts or pecans, cranberries, dates, almond pieces, whatever your heart desires!

directions.Direction: Add coconut cream, chocolate, coconut oil, nut butter, salt, and vanilla to a pot. Heat on low-medium/low until the chocolate is melted and everything is combined. Whisk frequently to encourage melting and mixing.
Add in the coconut flakes and any other add ins you're using.
Pour into a 9x9 greased baking dish and pop in the fridge to totally harden. You can also speed up the process by placing it in the freezer at first.
Cut into 16 even squares and
ENJOYYYY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: HEALTHY Chocolate Coconut Fudge
Description:
I'm absolutely obsessed with this recipe (and so is my husband) because it's DEEEEELISH and like actually kind of good for us.
High quality dark chocolate is full of antioxidants that can be essential during pregnancy, so this has been my go to dessert. 
You can mix and match the nut butters to make it your own, but I promise, it'll turn out amazing no matter what!
It is pretty smoooooshie, but hey, that's fudge!

ingredients.Name: pie crust, THE Pie Crust is perfect here so I'll add it, but use whatever you want!!
goat cheese, strawberry, plain, or whatever sweet flavor your want!
Melted butter or oil to prep the muffin tins

directions.Direction: Preheat the oven to 425F and prep the muffin tins. To do so I just brush the insides with some melted butter, but oil would work too!

Either roll out your pie crust or take the store bought crust out of its packaging. Make sure you have enough flour under the dough and on top so it doesn't stick when we cut out the rounds. Just a light dusting will do. We need TWELVE 3 1/2 inch-ish rounds so roll out the dough accordingly. An approximately 14-16 inch circle should do the trick.

Have some extra flour on hand to dust the cookie cutter if anything starts sticking. Cut out 12 rounds and then remove the excess pie crust. I keep a bag of "pie scraps" in my freezer so I always have some on hand for a quick appetizer or something.

Time to assemble! Smoosh 1 lil round into each of the 12 muffin holes. Use your finger to gently press the crust into the corners of the muffin tin; where the sides meet the bottom. This will help everything get nice and crispy!

Cut the goat cheese into 12 pieces. To do so just cut it in half length wise (hot dog), then in half length wise again so you should have 4 long strips of goat cheese. Then divide those into 3 pieces each. Then boom ya got 12 lil pieces.
Add 1 piece of goat cheese, 1 black berry, and 2 pecans to each lil pastry guy.
Bake at 425F for 18-22 minutes or until the blackberry is bubbly and the pastry is nice and golden.
Remove from the oven and drizzle each bite with some honey. No real amount here, just eyeball it and decide how much honey YOU want. It'll sorta sizzle and that just makes me happy.
Sprinkle A LITTLE flaky salt on each bite.
Remove them all from their tins and let cool ideally on a wire rack, but use whatever you have! They're best slightly warm, but will be delish no matter what.
ENJOY!!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Goat Chzzz Blackberry n' Pecan Pastry Bitez
Description:
The PERFECT apppy for this holiday season!!

Seriously they’re substantial enough to hold over your guests, but not toooooo hearty that they won’t want that delicious meal you’re still cooking. 

The mix between the buttery crust, creamy goat cheese, tart blackberries, crunchy pecans, sweet honey, n’ salty salt is PERFECTION. 🤌🏻

They’re SO EASY to make which is crucial during the holidays. Want to make it even easier? Swap out homemade crust for store bought! 

I used Vermont Creamery Strawberry Goat Cheese for this one, but you can of course use plain goat cheese! Maybe just add like a lil jam orrrr add a little extra honey to make up for the lost sweetness. It honestly doesn't matter, however you do it will be amazing!!

This recipe is so so so easy to double, triple, or whatever you need!!! Just make sure you have enough muffin tins. ;)
Notes:
* If you don't have a cookie cutter don't fret! You more than likely have an aluminum can of something in your pantry. Just remove the contents of the can (but save them of course don't go wasting food), the paper on the outside, and remove BOTH the top and bottom aluminum. and then boom. there you have your brand new and super fancy cookie cutter. 
* Can you freeze them? Well idk yet but that's what I'm doing! I made the whole batch and immediately froze them. I plan on letting them thaw then reheating in a 325F oven for about 10 minutes just to bring life back to them. I won't be placing them back in a tin, just reheating on a cookie sheet.

directions.Direction: Preheat your oven to 325 F and line a baking sheet with parchment paper.

In a heat proof bowl, melt 2 tbsp ghee, then add 2 tbsp good quality honey, 1/4 tsp smoked paprika, and 1/2 tsp diamond crystal kosher salt. Mixie mix. Then add in 16oz raw, whole cashews. Mixie mix. Then spread evenly on the baking sheet. Sprinkle with some extra smoked pap if you’re feeling crazy.

Bake for 20 minutes for golden, 25 for deeply golden, and 30 for super golden and very smoky. Choose your adventure. Toss once out of the oven, allow to cool, then eat those suckers up. You can top with more salt if that’s your vibe.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Smoky Honey Roasted Cashews w/ Ghee
Description: Ok these are sooooo easy and the perfect healthy snack to keep ya goin. Loaded with ghee and honey, they’re salty, sweet, smoky, and addictive.

ingredients.Name: Fresh cracked black pep, more for topping
Juice o’  lemon, or to taste

directions.Direction: Literally put everything except flaky salt into a food processor and process until super duper smooth. Scrape and taste as you go!!
Depending on how intense your tomatoes are you may need extra sugar.
Top with extra olive oil, paprika, flaky salt, and some fresh cracked black pep. So easy. ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Sun dried tomato HUMMUS
Description: Unless you’re buying organic hummus you’re eating a butt ton of glyphosates. Soooo to combat that and personalize my hummus I just make it myself. Seems extra until you do it and realize how freaking easy and cheap it is. Bon appetit baby.

directions.Direction: Place eggs in a pot and cover with water, making sure to cover with at least 1 inch of water over the top of the eggs. Cover and bring to a boil. Once boiling turn off the heat and let the eggs cook for 10 minutes.
Immediately after the 10 minutes remove the eggs from the water and place them in a bowl filled with water and ice. Let them cook for at least 15 minutes.
Once cooled, gently tap the egg on the side of the bowl or counter and peel away the shell. Use the water to help you get the shell to remove cleanly.

Cut all of the eggs in half. Pop out the yolks and place them in a separate bowl. Give the egg whites one more rinse under water to make sure they are clean and no yolk remains (it's ok if some remains inside the hole since we'll be filling that anyways).

Add all other ingredients (aside from chives) to the egg yolk bowl. You can use a fork to mash it up, but the best way to do this is to use an immersion blender. If you don't have an immersion blender you could also use a bullet blender! Mix until everything is fully incorporated and no yellow yolk remains.
Fill a piping bag or a ziplock bag with the egg mixture. Cut off the tip/corner to produce a 1/2-3/4in round opening. Evenly pipe the egg mixture into each egg white hole.
Top with some thinly sliced chives and let fully chill before serving.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Beet Deviled Eggs
Description:
What is an Easter Dinner without some deviled eggs? 

I am a huge fan of deviled eggs and am constantly trying to find new ways to jazz them up. I’ve done beet pickled eggs before (spoiler alert, they’re amazing), but I wanted to do something visually different. 

Bring in beet deviled eggs! They have a vibrant red color that really pops against the white. And don’t be surprised, these are HEAVY on the beet flavor. 

Aside from the addition of powdered beet they’re actually an extremely common deviled egg recipe.

ingredients.Name: of puff pastry If you use THE Flaky Pie Crust follow the directions for rough puff and use the entire double batch.
medium yellow onions, peeled and thinly sliced

directions.Direction: Prep the puff pastry or pie crust. Oil a baking sheet and line with parchment paper. We're baking it in a half sheet tray (aka what you probably think of when you think "cookie sheet"). Make sure the dimensions of the dough are 16x12ish and that it will fit in whatever baking sheet you're using. If you used THE Flaky Pie Crust (good for you!!! you won't regret that extra little bit of work) just roll out the WHOLE batch of dough instead of cutting it in half and making 2 pie crusts. Use a pastry cutter or knife to score the outside 1/2 in of the crust (this creates a "crust") and a fork to dock the entire center. Put in the fridge to stay chill.
Preheat oven to 425F. Once preheated bake the prepped pie crust for 15 minutes or until starting to turn golden and crispy. Remove from the oven and set aside.

While the pie is chilling and baking you can prepare the other components. First let's do the onions. Set a medium sized skillet over medium heat. Melt 1 tbsp of butter and add in the sliced onions. You may have to toggle between medium, medium-high, and medium-low to keep them from charring yet still cooking down. You want to cook them for about 40 minutes or until they're your desired level of softened and caramelized. Feel free to stop at 20 minutes if you just don't feel like going to "proper" caramelized level, trust me they'll be fine.
Add into the balsamic, stir, and let it reduce into the onions. It should only take 1-3 minutes. Remove onions and set aside.

Add another tbsp of butter to the pan and cook the sliced mushrooms. Let these cook undisturbed in the pan for 4-7 minutes - you want nice and golden crispy on that first side before you stir them. Stir and cook another 3-5 minutes or until all of the moisture appears to have evaporated out. Remove mushrooms and set aside.
Using a food processor or blender, add goat cheese, yogurt, 2 tbsp of the caramelized onions, honey, and some pepper. Process until totally smooth.

To assemble: dump the goat cheese mixture onto the pie crust. Use a spoon to evenly disperse. I know it may seem runny, but trust me it'll firm up while in the oven. Evenly spread out the onions and mushrooms on top.
Bake at 425F for 15-20 minutes or until the goat cheese has clearly firmed up and the edges of the crust seem super golden and crispy. No soggy bottoms here.
Once out of the oven top with fresh thyme leaves, an extra drizzle of honey, and some flaky salt.
Cut into however many portions you want, but I think 12 works nicely.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Caramelized Onion and Mushroom Goat Cheese Tart
Description:
Sometimes I make a recipe that even shocks me… this was one of those. 

I envisioned this recipe as a starter for your Easter Dinner, but it would be totally perfect at the main table as well. 

This Caramlized Onion and Mushroom Goat Cheese Tart starts off with my all butter pie crust that I turn into a rough puff (I’ll give details in the recipe online!)

The sauce is goat cheese with plain yog. 
And we top it with some caramelized onions turned balsamic reduction onions and some pan fried portobello mushrooms. 

You absolutely need to make this for your Easter Dinner or literally just any day you want a flavor explosion in your mouth.

ingredients.Name: dried rosemary or 1/2 tsp fresh and finely chopped rosemary

directions.Direction: Add almonds, olive oil, garlic powder, onion powder, rosemary, and some salt and pep to a pan. Cook over medium-low for about 5-7 minutes, stirring frequently, until they become fragrant. Keep an eye on them and adjust the temp up or down depending on what you observe.
Add in the smoked paprika and continue to cook for 1 minute.
Remove from the heat and add to a bowl.
While that's cooking chop up the cheddar into tiny cubes. Add the cheddar to the bowl of almonds along with the hot honey.
Mixie mix, taste for salt level, and
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Sweet Smokey Cheddar Almonds
Description:
These may be my all time favorite snack. They're the perfect balance of sweet, salty, smokey, creamy, and crunchy. Plus, they're PACKED with protein. 

When I first started posting videos to social media I really wanted to share this recipe and thought it would be "too boring". Entertainment aside, you need to make these.
They store beautifully in the fridge and make the perfect afternoon or lunchtime snack.
Notes:
- Since this has cheese make sure you store it in the fridge in an airtight container. Let FULLY cool before storing it.
- If you don't have hot honey you can make it by combining 1 tbsp honey with 1/8 tsp chili crisp or hot sauce

ingredients.Name: asparagus (12 oz), cut into 2 in sections
roasted and salted shelled pistachios, roughly chopped
heaping tbsp honey or maple syrup
A little fresh cracked black pepper

directions.Direction: Bring a pot of water to a boil. Once boiling add in asparagus and peas. Let simmer for 3 minutes and then immediately remove and place in a bowl of ice water to cool.
Use a bullet blender to combine olive oil, vinegar, mustard, honey, garlic, salt, and pepper. Let that mix until the whole mixture is emulsified.
Assembly: Add the whole bag of spinach leaves to a large serving platter (you can use a bowl, but I think platters make for a better presentation).

Add the drained and dried asparagus and peas on top. I like to sort of fluff up the spinach towards the end of adding the asparagus and peas, then fill in sections with peas. It'll just makes the salad seem even more substantial.
Top with feta, then pistachios, then dressing.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Asparagus and Pea Spinach Salad
Description:
Perfect for my Easter Series 🐰

It takes advantage of Spring produce and brings something bright and fresh to the table. 
PLUS it's insanely quick to throw together. The asparagus and peas get blanched to soften them and bring out their color, but that's what takes the longest (and it's 3 minutes...) Anddd while that's boiling you can make the dressing so realistically, you could get this together in 10-20 minutes. 

The feta gives it the perfect amount of creaminess without weighing anything down. 
The pistachios give crunch, saltiness, and of course extra fat. 

It just might be my new hyper-fixation salad.

ingredients.Name: Cotija or Queso Fresca, crumbled, plus more for topping
olive oil, plus more for corn

directions.Direction: Preheat grill or grill pan to char the corn. The exact heat/temp will depend on your cooking apparatus so go with whatever you feel will yield you a light char on the corn.
Prep corn by drizzling olive oil all over and seasoning with salt and pepper. I like to do this in a baking sheet so I can just spin the corn around and make sure all sides are coated and seasoned.
Cook corn for 5-10 minutes, rotating occasionally, until all sides of the corn are either cooked or lightly charred.
Let cool and then use a knife to cut off the corn kernels.

In a small pan heat olive oil over medium heat. Add in cumin seeds and smoked paprika and cook for 1-2 minutes - just until "bloomed" and fragrant. You do NOT want to burn the spices! We're just extracting flavor and making a spiced olive oil.

Add spiced olive oil to a large bowl and mix in the other wet ingredients to create a sauce. You need about 2-4 tbsp lime juice so juice accordingly - I suggest going on the lighter end, tasting the final product, and then adjusting to your taste preference.
Add in all of the remaining ingredients, mix to combine, and taste for seasoning. You may need to add extra salt and/or lime juice.

You can eat this straight away, but I find letting it sit and chill for at least an hour helps marry the flavors together and the chill makes it all the more pleasant. Top with some extra cotija just to make it pretty.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Elote Style Corn Salad
Description:
Is it a salad? Is it salsa? Is it a topping? Listen it is whatever you want it to be.

This Elote Style Corn Salad is the perfect accompaniment to any meal you're having. It's perfectly balanced with some warming spices, cooling sour cream, and bright herbs and onions. 

Plus it comes together in 20 minutes and requires minimal cleanup. 

It's potluck party DREAMS!

ingredients.Name: Pickle De Gallo, plus more for topping

directions.Direction: Heat 1 tbsp olive oil (you can also use tallow, ghee, camel, etc) in a large dutch oven over medium-high heat.

Once hot, add in the ground beef in chunks. You want to evenly distribute the chunks on the bottom of the pot, trying to maintain some space between each piece so they can properly brown and not steam. Season with salt and pepper. Allow to cook for 3-5 minutes, or until the bottoms are deeply browned and crispy.

Use a spatula or spoon to break up the pieces of meat and mix around. It’s ok if a small amount of pink remains as the meat will continue to cook in the sauce in a little bit. Remove with a slotted spoon and set aside.

Add the onion and garlic to the pot and fry in the leftover beef fat for about 3-5 minutes, or until softened and edges starting to brown. Push over to one side, add the other 1 tbsp olive oil, and add the tomato paste to that.
Let the tomato paste cook, moving it around frequently, until it goes from a bright cherry red color to a darker almost brick color. Then stir the onions and tomato paste together.
Immediately pour in the diced tomatoes, beef, and pickle de Gallo and brine. Stir to combine and let simmer on medium-low for about 5 minutes.
In the meantime, you want to be cooking your pasta in heavily salted water! Cook until just under al dente, as it’ll continue to cook in the sauce.

Once the pasta is cooked to the desired texture, use a spider to transfer it from the water to the sauce. You’ll likely bring some pasta water over with the noodles and thats perfectly fine! We actually want to add 1 cup of pasta water in addition!!

Stir everything together, then add in the cheese. Stir until everything is melted and the sauce is emulsifying. Let simmer on medium-low for about 5 minutes, just to encourage everything to come together more.
Plate with extra pickle de Gallo on top and
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Hamburger Pasta with Grillo’s Pickle De Gallo 🥒🔥
Description:
It’s everything you want in a hamburger, but pastafied!! 😎

The addish of Grillo's Pickles Pickle De Gallo brightens up the entire dish and brings a briney n’ bright flavor!

It’s bringing all those yummy cozy nostalgic feelz with a new and delish twist.

ingredients.Name: can tomatoes (fire roasted is great but whole peeled is good too)
can black beans, drained and rinsed
can kidney beans, drained and rinsed
limes, one juiced one cut into quarters

directions.Direction: Heat a large dutch oven over medium-high heat.

Add olive oil and ground beef. You want to break the beef up into chunks, trying to spread it out evenly on the bottom of the pot, but not crowding the pieces. You want to make sure there is a little space between the bits to encourage browning and NOT steaming!
Season with salt and pepper and allow to cook for about 3-5 minutes, or until that first side is deeply browned and crisping.

Flip over all the bits and break everything up into smaller pieces. Continue to stir around and cook for another 1-2 minutes, or until the majority of the pink is gone. You don’t want to take it too far because it’ll continue to cook later in the chili. Use a slotted spoon or strainer to remove the beef and set it aside. Lower the heat to medium.

Add onions and red pepper (jalapeños too if using) to the dutch oven (into all that delicioussss beef fat) and cook for about 5-7 minutes. You want the onion pretty darn translucent and edges starting to brown.

Add in garlic, lentils, chili powder, oregano, cumin, and salt. Stir that around for about one minute to bloom/toast the spices, then pour in the 4 cups of water. Mixie mix and place the lid on to cook for about 15 minutes. Stir occasionally and lower the heat to whatever is a gentle simmer for you (medium / medium-low)

Add in the tomatoes (if you’re using whole peeled just mash it up with your hands), beans, and beef and return the chili to a gentle simmer. Let that cook for about 20-30 minutes or until it has thickened and beans are beginning to burst.

Turn off the heat and add in the juice of 1 lime, 1 tbsp maple syrup, and give that a mixie mix. Taste the chili and adjust for seasoning - aka extra salt, extra maple syrup, extra lime, or that extra 2 tbsp chili powder!
In my opinion, it is a MUST to top the chili with sharp cheddar cheese, then plain whole milk green yogurt, thennn some cilantro, and maybe an extra squeeze of lime juice.
It is best when eaten with fresh cornbread or tortillas.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Super Protein Chili
Description:
It’s cozy, it’s filling, it’s chocked full of protein and meal prep friendly. 
IT’S CHILI! 🔥

I pack this one with beans, lentils, and ground beef to really load it with protein. And even though I personally omit jalapeños, they’re obviously a welcome addish if your body loves spice. 

I really like to use fire roasted tomatoes here for extra flavor, but normal ol’ tomatoes will be just fine!

ingredients.Name: rice wine vinegar (can sub for white wine vinegar or ACV)
zucchini, sliced into 1/2 in thick half moons
Some thickkk Noods  I used 2 packs of Thai Wheat Noodles from @traderjoes

directions.Direction: Cook yo noodz in a pot of heavily salted water. While that's cooking you can prepare you sauce and prepare green onions.

To prepare the green onions: The whites will be thinly sliced into rounds and greens sliced into strips. Basically just slice the greens lengthwise as thinly as you can. Then take all of those strips and plunge them in ice cold water and they will turn into lil green onion spirals!
Mixie mix all sauce ingredients in a medium sized bowl. Set aside.
Set a skillet over medium heat, add oil, and cook zucchini and WHITE PARTS of the green onions until the zucchini is softened and starting to brown.

Just push the veg over to the side, and use the remaining pan space to fry your egg. You may want to turn up the heat a bit, but add some extra oil, crack the egg in, and cook to your desired doneness. I like over medium so about 2 minutes on each side. Fry as many eggs as you are making individual serving bowls!
Remove the eggs but leave the veg! Add in the noodlez, sauce, and mixie mix to combine.
Top with egg, the spiral green onions, and any other fun toppings you like! Hot sauce, sesame seeds, furikake, you name it!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Peanuttty NOODZ
Description:
Comes together extremely fast and is outrageously delicious!
Plus you get to make fun lil curly green onions and that's always a win :)

ingredients.Name: unsalted butter 3/4 stick: cut into 1 tbsp chunks
freshly grated parm, plus more for topping

directions.Direction: Cook noodlez in heavily salted water until just under al dente, they’ll continue cooking in the sauce. Reserve 2 1/2 cups pasta water for the sauce and of course a leeetle extra for just in case.

Add the 2 1/2 cups pasta water to a large pan (stainless steel skillet). Heat over medium-high until you reach a gentle simmer. Then add in one tbsp piece of butter at a time, whisking constantly and making sure it is fully melted/incorporated before adding the next one. Once all of the butter is in and emulsifying, slowwwwwly add in your parm. Once again, whisking constantly.

Plop in your noodz and mix, stir, shake, twirl, spin until the sauce is clinging to the noodz, about 3 minutes. If you take the sauce too far and it’s getting dry n sticky, just add some of that “just in case” pasta water and let it come back together.
Serve with a drizz of lemon juice, some lemon zest, extra parm doiii, flaky salt, black pep, and a drizz of olive oil.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Pappardelle Alfredo
Description:
It’s like Fettuccini Alfredo, but obvs pappardelle with like a pasta al limone twist. So idk call it whatever you want, it’s delish. 

Basically to make a legit alfredo you just need water, butter, and parm. So dats what we’re doing… but adding some pizazz. 

Let’s get it 🔥

ingredients.Name: 1/2ish cup vodka (let’s be honest I was just pouring…)
1/3ish cup freshly grated parm, plus more for topping
Toppings: Basil, Parm, Flaky Salt, Pepper, Olive Oil

directions.Direction: Cook pasta in HEAVILY salted water until just under al dente. It’ll finish cooking in the sauce a bit. Make sure to reserve 1/4 cup of pasta water.

Heat a couple tablespoons of oil in a dutch oven over medium heat. Add onions and garlic and cook for about 6-8 minutes, stirring frequently. Season with salt n pep. You want these to slowly soften and brown. Add in red pepper flakes and anchovy filets (please just add them… believe in me here) and stir to break up the chovies and toast the red pep.
Pour in the vodka, stir to combine, and use your spoon to scrape up all those wonderful brown bitz stuck to the bottom of the pot. Cause dats flavor baby. Let all of that evaporate out.
Add the whole 6oz can of tomato paste and cook for 2-3 minutes, or until it goes from bright red to like brick red. Ya feel me?

Ok so now you need that 1/4 cup reserved pasta water, to that add your 3/4 cup heavy cream (this will help it from seizing and breaking in the hot pan). Slowwwwly add in the cream mix to the pot and stir to combine. Add the 1/3ish cup grated parm, mixie mix.
Use a spider/strainer to add cooked pasta to the dutch oven. We’re trying to get some pasta water to transfer over too. Mixie mix, taste for seasoning and adjust accordingly.
Highly recommend topping it with basil, parm, drizzle of olive oil, flaky salt, and more pep.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Rigatoni Alla VODKA
Description: A little spicy, a little umami wit the chovies… it’s my perfect vodka sauce.

ingredients.Name: elbow macaroni, or whatever pasta shape makes you happy
dill pickle spears, diced into 1/2 in cubes
chives, chopped into teeny tiny chive tubes

directions.Direction: Boil pasta in heavily salted water according to package directions or until tender. Drain and set aside.
While the pasta is cooking prep/cut all of your vegetables.

In a large mixing bowl combine the ingredients for the sauce. Mayo, vinegar, coconut sugar, milk, pickle juice, salt, and pepper. Whisk until no clumps remain. Taste test for seasoning and keep in mind that it's seasoning the pasta and all of the other toppings so you want it to be really bright.

Add the cooked pasta and all of the cut of veggies to the sauce mixture. Mix to combine. Once again taste for seasoning and adjust accordingly. You can always add extra milk if you want more sauce, pickle juice for brininess, sugar for sweetness, and salt for saltiness.
Allow to chill, covered, for at least an hour, but ideally 2+ so that it fully chills and all of the flavors combine.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: THE Pasta Salad
Description:
This is day one of my Easter Series and I knew I had to kick it off with a rendition of my mom’s pasta salad. 👏🏻

This dish was such a staple in our home and surely graced many Easter spreads over the years. 🐣

Without fail my mom’s pasta salad always had carrots, celery, and black olives, but the addition of radish and pickles do something really special here. 

This isn’t the super soupy, mayo overload pasta salad that you remember. This is perfectly balanced with a light coating of that creamy, sweet, and tangy sauce. 
This is sure to please any pasta salad lover!

ingredients.Name: peanut butter (or any nut butter you like!)
heaping cup nuts and seeds (any combo you have, but I did walnuts, almonds, sunflower seeds, and pumpkin seeds)

directions.Direction: Add everything to a food processor
Blend for 2-4 minutes. It’ll seem like a long time, but this will give all of the nuts and seeds ample time to break down and sorta turn into their own butter.
Divide into 1 1/2 in balls - it should yield around 24 ballz.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Chocolate Peanut Butter Nut n’ Seed Protein Ballz
Description:
An easy peasy lil food prep that gives you healthy protein snacks at any time you need. 

They’re easily adaptable to whatever nut and seed or nut butter options you have in your pantry, so don’t stress if you don’t have the exact same ingredients. And if you don't have something, just riff and replace/remove it. It may not be perfect, but it'll be pretty darn close!

ALSOOO they get better and hold better together as they sit in the fridge.

ingredients.Name: Frescatrano or Castelvetrano Olives, drained but liquid reserved
chili flakes (I used Korean chili flakes)
Leaves from  sprigs of thyme (1ish tsp)

directions.Direction: Mixie mix everything in a bowl and add olives. The longer they sit the more marinated and punchy they get!

If you’re eating them immediately just discard the reserved olive liquid, but if you want to keep these in the fridge you can add the marinated olives back to their jar and top it off with the reserved liquid.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Citrus Marinated OLIVES
Description:
Snack game just got three strong.

Ok but seriously these are also AMAZING for a charcootie board or appetizer spread. They’re punchy, buttery, and bright.

directions.Direction: Put everything in a food processor (starting with only 1/4 cup nut butter) and blitz until it starts sticking together and forming a ball in the mixer. If it doesn’t seem to be mixing well add the additional 1/4 cup nut butter.
Using a small cookie scoop (or a spoon) scoop out approximately 1 tbsp sized portions.
Roll in your palms to warm it up and smooth it out, then roll those in the coconut shreds.
Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator and eat within ideally a week.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Superfood Protein ENERGY ballzzzz
Description: These suckers are so good to prep and leave in the fridge for whenever you need that lil afternoon pick me up. They’re also perfect after a workout for a quick protein BOOOOST. Heck, eat em for brekkie. There’s no wrong way to do it.

ingredients.Name: 1/4ish cup yellow or dijon mustard (you're just squirting/squeezing it on so don't think about it too much)

directions.Direction: Heat up a medium sized skillet over medium/high heat with your added oil.
While that heats up you can prepare your pickle spear snacks. Lay out all 6 slices of ham, top each with a piece of swiss cheese, then a pickle spear, and a line of mustard.
Roll the spears up and let them lay on the seam side. I used a lil toothpick to help secure them for their initial cook.
Cook first on that seam side to help close it. Cook for about 4 minutes or until browning and crisping.

So here's the deal, these get messy. You'll probably think you're doing something wrong because the cheese kind melts out and cooks on the pan, the mustard sizzles, WORRY NOT! It is all part of the plan. The cheese bubbling out and crisping helps give us extra lil crispy bits once fully cooked and cooled. So just trust the process and keep going.
Remove the toothpicks and cook on the other side for another 4ish minutes. You want everything nice and crispy, so feel free to flip again and do what you gotta do.
Remember, these will firm up once cooled. So just do your best to separate the cheese and remove each lil snack and put it on a plate to cool.
After about 5 minutes these should have firmed up and cooled down to the point where you aren't eating boiling hot cheese and pickle lava.
Once again you can dip in something else, but I think they're perfect just how they are.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Crispy Ham n' Cheese Pickle Spears
Description:
These are the perfect little appetizer. You just grab em and go! 
They're crispy, they're salty, they're cheesy, they're PICKLEY!

There's mustard right on in them to give them that extra tangy bite, but you can of course pair this with a dip sauce if that tickles your fancy. 

Can literally make however many you want. Just eating this as a lil snack for you? Make 1 or 2. Want leftovers? Go for 6. Feeding a big ol' crowed? Cook the whole dang jar!

ingredients.Name: 4, springs lavender plus more for garnish

directions.Direction: Make the honey lavender simple syrup: combine honey, water, lavender, and 3-4 slices smoked lemon.
To a shaker bottle or mason jar add 5oz lemon juice, 3oz honey lavender simple syrup, 8oz dry gin. So 1 part lemon + honey, 1 part gin.
Add ice to your shaker bottle, put on the lid, and shake dat up until the bottle is cold.
Strain into a coupe glass and garnish with another lemon slice and sprig of lavender.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Honey Lavender Smokey Bees Knees
Description: Ahhhh the classic "Bees Knees" I love so much, but done extra special. We make a smokey lavender simple syrup jazz dat baby up.

ingredients.Name: lemons, 1 sliced and smoked/dehydrated, 1 cut half
Orange Peach Mango Aqua Kefir (Trader Joes but sub with Kombucha)

directions.Direction: Make the honey simple syrup. Combine honey, boiling water, and sliced ginger.
To a shaker glass, add the juice of 1 lemon (about 3 tablespoons), juice of 1/2 grapefruit (about 3 tablespoons), and 1/4 cup simple syrup, and some ice.
Shake that bad boy up until the glass is cold and the mix is frothyyyyyy.
Pour into a champagne coupe until 1/2 way full and top the remainder with the aqua kefir.
Garnish with a smoked lemon slice.
****WANT BOOZE?! Skip the aqua kefir and sub DRY GIN.

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: It's the Beez Kneez!
Description: A riff on the classic "Bees Knees" but this time with hydrating ingredients and probiotics!

directions.Direction: Start by making the honey simple syrup. Combine honey, water, and the sliced ginger.
To a shaker glass add ginger cube, a splash of boiling water to dissolve it, and blackberries. Muddle those until mushy.
Add the ashwagandha, mixie mix.
Then add the juice of 1 lime, about 3 tablespoons.
Add in Power Purple juice and 1/4 cup of the simple syrup (or to your liking)
Add some ice cubes and shake that baby up until the shaker bottle is cold.
Pour into a glass full of ice and top with a blackberry and some lime zest.
***WANT ALCOHOL?! Sub 1/2 of the purple juice for TEQUILLAAAAA*

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Purple Blackberry Elixer
Description: Cuz sometimes you’re just craving the color purple ya know? It’s a lil spicy with the ginger, relaxing with ashwagandha, and just a powerhouse cuz we use some “Power Purple” Trader Joe’s drank. It's alcohol free, but can easily be made booze included!

directions.Direction: Add lychee and yuzu juice to a shaker bottle and muddle that up to release the lychee juice.

Add in the honey and coconut water, throw in some ice cubzzz, and place the lid on TIGHTLY. We don’t need a mess here. Shake that up until it is nice and frothy, the outside of the shaker is cooooold, and honey is dissolved.
Fill two small cups with ice, strain and divide juice mix evenly between the two cups, and top with kombucha. I garnished with a little basil leaf/flower but you can use whatever makes you happy.
ENJOY!

Creator: thetessasmith
Name: Lychee n’ Yuzu Barbie Mocktail
Description:
Barbie pink is blassssting off right now, so how about a super duper hydrating and refreshing Lychee n’ Yuzu Barbie mocktail?! I just feel cute saying it👼🏻

This lil drink is JAM PACKED with healthy things for ya. Coconut water for hydration, kombucha for gut health, honey for immunity… and lychee n’ yuzu are both major power houses. 🌸🌼

ingredients.Name: Extra salt and pep for seasoning
A bundle of herbs (rosemary, thyme, sage) plus more for around the pan

directions.Direction: I feel like for step one you should just take a moment to be proud of yourself for embarking on the journey of making THE Thanksgiving turkey. Idk about for you but that can be an intimidating task. So yeah, step one: pat yourself on the back.

Ok but let's get into it. We want to dry brine the turkey. IDEALLY this will happen overnight or even 2 days in advance (don't go over that). This serves a couple purposes. 1. It will season the bird inside and out. 2. It draws excess moisture out so that when you cook it the skin gets a burnish color and crisps up. To dry brine you just pop the turkey on a rimed baking sheet with a wire rack inside, make sure to remove any neck/giblets from the inside and set those aside for stock. Mixie mix the salt, sugar, and black pepper and then sprinkle that all over the exterior of the turkey and thennnn once it's sufficiently covered, just pour the remainder in. n' that's it. Place the bird in the fridge UNCOVERED for your desired time. And hear me out... I've been in a turkey pickle, a turkey... emergency before on Thanksgiving and only dry brined for like 2 hours. It's not ideal, but it's better than nothin.

Ok it's thanksgiving day. It's happening. Remove the bird from the oven about 2 hours prior to baking. This will just help the temperature level out and ensure you get even baking. But about 30 minutes before you're ready to pop it in we can preheat the oven and dress it up. (PREHEAT TO 425F) I remove the wire rack, pour out the excess liquid on the rimmed baking sheet, and then just plop the turkey back down on the baking sheet.

Here is the weird part. You want to separate the skin from the breast muscle. Go to the cavity of the turkey and insert your finger(s) between the skin and the breast muscle. You'll have to work your whole hand in to go the length of the breast.

Once the skin is separated just pour some of the melted butter in between, insert your hand between again to smear it around, then pour the butter allllll over the exterior of the turkey! Really making sure that the exterior of the breast and drums get coated.

Then insert 1 onion, 1 head of garlic, the lemon, and bundle of herbs into the cavity of the turkey. Look at the notes below for "bundle of herbs" clarification. Then scatter remaining onions, garlic, and ADDITIONAL herbs all around the turkey on the bottom of the baking sheet.

I then drizzle olive oil all over the sheet pan aromatics andddd on top of the turkey for extra browning power. And just cuz I can't help myself, I season the outside of the bird and sheet pan aromatics with some fresh cracked salt and black pep. Cuz seasoning!
OK THE OVEN IS PREHEATED TO 425F. THE TURKEY IS DRY BRINED, BUTTERED, AND FILLED WITH AROMATICS. IT'S TIME BABY!

Pop dat turkey in the oven at 425F for a total of 30 minutes at that temp. We want to bake for 15, then rotate for even browning, then another 15 minutes. I like to do a higher temp at the beginning to encourage browning BUTTTT we don't want that high temp at the end of the cooking time because let's be honest, there's gonna be other stuff in the oven that you don't want to overcook ya feel me?

After the 30 minutes at 425F you want to lower the temp to 325F and continue cooking until an instant read thermometer reads 160-165F when inserted into the THICKEST part of the breast. I say 160F is okkkkk because it'll continue to warm up as it rests, but if you want to be totally safe just go until 165F. Rotate the bird every 45-60 minutes to check on it and rotate it.
*** COOKING TIME: As a general rule you can expect to cook for 15 minutes for every pound of meat. Butttt we're cooking at a higher temp at first so just keep that in mind. ***
AFTER 1 HOUR: you want to pour 1-2 cups of water into the baking sheet. This will help keep the aromatics from burning annnnnd give us a hefty amount of "stock" for gravy.

Once you hit that internal temp of 165F remove the bird from the oven and let rest on a separate baking sheet for AT LEAST 1 HOUR, but don't go over 2 1/2 hours. And if it's your first time cutting a turkey I highhhhly recommend watching some YouTube videos. Or ya know, just dive in.
I say separate baking sheet because you're gonna want all those pan juices for gravy. So if you're making THE Gravy, just move onto that. :) Otherwise. Wait for your turkey to cool, cut, and
ENJOY!!

Name: THE Thanksgiving Turkey
Description:
You know I'm happy with a recipe when I coin it "THE" recipe. I'm not kidding here. This is THE Turkey recipe you need. 

It's simple, easy to follow, AND I structured the temperature so that you have a steady 325F and can cook/reheat your other sides at the same time. Cuz idk about you, but there certainly isn't just turkey in my oven on Thanksgiving day, m'kay?

It comes out with a deeply golden skin, a hefty sheet pan of juices for stock, and moist n' tender skin. The only thing that makes this turkey better is THE Gravy to go with it. 

I'll create a separate recipe that links them both :) 

COOKING TIME: As a general rule you can expect to cook for 15 minutes for every pound of meat. Butttt we're cooking at a higher temp to start so just keep that in mind.
Notes:
*Pro tip! Use the neck and giblets that you remove when you are dry brining the turkey to make a stock. (You'll need stock the next day for gravy!) I like to just add any veggie scraps I have accumulated, but you can be safe with some carrots, celery, any herbs you have, onion, garlic... you know... stock things. Just pop that all in a crock pot and let it go overnight. You'll thank yourself the next day!
*"Bundle of Herbs": I use rosemary, sage, and thyme. About 2 sprigs of rosemary, 4 sprigs of sage, and an equal in proportion amount of thyme. Just use some kitchen twine to tie those together. 
*COOKING TIME: As a general rule you can expect to cook for 15 minutes for every pound of meat. Butttt we're cooking at a higher temp to start so just keep that in mind.

ingredients.Name: pie crust, THE Pie Crust is perf here!
butter, ghee, or oil of choice
leftover turkey, chopped (light and dark meat are perf)

directions.Direction: Preheat oven to 425F

Heat butter in a large cast iron pan or stainless steel pan. I use an 11in cast iron with 2in walls and bake the entire pot pie it. You can also bake in deep dish pie plate... but who wants to dirty more dishes?
Once melted add in onion, carrot, and celery. Season with salt and pep. Cook those until the onions are turning translucent and beginning to brown. 5-7 minutes.
Add in peas, turkey, and thyme leaves. Mixie mix to combine.
Now we get jiggy wit it. Add in the gravy, broth, and heavy cream. Allow that to heat up until the gravy is fully incorporated. Taste it and test for seasoning. Add extra salt n’ pep to adjust!
Place the cast iron skillet on a rimmed baking sheet. If you aren't using your cast iron just pour the mixture into whatever vessel you're baking it in and then put that on top of the baking sheet.

Place crust on top of the pie plate (you want the pie crust to be about 1-2in larger than the top width of your skillet). Tuck the extra edges under and working QUICKLY, tuck them under and use a fork to press into the pie plate. Just try to avoid dough overhang as it'll just melt off. Cut 1-4 vents in the top of your pie crust and pop dat in the oven!
Immediately lower the temp to 375F and bake for 45-55 minutes or until the top is nice and golden and the filling is bubbbbbbbly!
Allow to cool for a bit before diving in so you don’t absotootly destroy your mouth, but then that’s it!
ENJOY!

Notes: *If you don't have that much or ANY gravy, just sub the amount with stock. IF YOU DO THAT though, just make sure to add 2 tbsp of flour to the carrot, celery, onion mixture at the end of its cooking time.
